# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: infertility
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Abortion continues to be a controversial subject in many societies on religious, moral, ethical, practical, and political grounds.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Though it has been banned and otherwise limited by law in many jurisdictions, abortions continue to be common in many areas, even where they are illegal.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] According to a 2007 study conducted by the Guttmacher Institute and the World Health Organization, abortion rates are similar in countries where the procedure is legal and in countries where it is not, due to unavailability of modern contraceptives in areas where abortion is illegal.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Also according to the study, the number of abortions worldwide is declining due to increased access to contraception.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Abortion has existed since ancient times, with natural abortifacients being found amongst a wide variety of tribal people and in most written sources.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] The earliest known records of abortion techniques and general reproductive regulation date as far back as 2700 BC in China, and 1550 BC in Egypt.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Early texts contain little mention of abortion or abortion law.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] When it does appear, it is entailed in concerns about male property rights, preservation of social order, and the duty to produce fit citizens for the state or community.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] The harshest penalties were generally reserved for a woman who procured an abortion against her husband's wishes, and for slaves who produced abortion in a woman of high status.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Religious texts often contained severe condemnations of abortion, recommending penance but seldom enforcing secular punishment.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] As a matter of common law in England and the United States, abortion was illegal anytime after quickening—when the movements of the fetus could first be felt by the woman.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Under the born alive rule, the fetus was not considered a "reasonable being" *in rerum natura*; and abortion was not treated as murder in English law.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] In the 19th century, many Western countries began to codify abortion laws or place further restrictions on the practice.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Anti-abortion movements were led by a combination of groups opposed to abortion on moral grounds, and by medical professionals who were concerned about the danger presented by the procedure and the regular involvement of non-medical personnel in performing abortions.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Nevertheless, it became clear that illegal abortions continued to take place in large numbers even where abortions were rigorously restricted.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] It was difficult to obtain sufficient evidence to prosecute the women and abortion doctors, and judges and juries were often reluctant to convict.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] For example, Henry Morgentaler, a Canadian pro-choice advocate, was never convicted by a jury.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] He was acquitted by a jury in the 1973 court case, but the acquittal was overturned by five judges on the Quebec Court of Appeal in 1974.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] He went to prison, appealed, and was again acquitted.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] In total, he served 10 months, suffering a heart attack while in solitary confinement.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Many were also outraged at the invasion of privacy and the medical problems resulting from abortions taking place illegally in medically dangerous circumstances.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Political movements soon coalesced around the legalization of abortion and liberalization of existing laws.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] By the first half of the 20th century, many countries had begun to liberalize abortion laws, at least when performed to protect the woman's life and in some cases on the woman's request.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Under Vladimir Lenin, the Soviet Union became the first modern state in legalizing abortions on request—the law was first introduced in the Russian SFSR in 1920, in the Ukrainian SSR in July 1921, and then in the whole country.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] The Bolsheviks saw abortion as a social evil created by the capitalist system, which left women without the economic means to raise children, forcing them to perform abortions.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] The Soviet state initially preserved the tsarist ban on abortion, which treated the practice as premeditated murder.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] However, abortion had been practiced by Russian women for decades and its incidence skyrocketed further as a result of the Russian Civil War, which had left the country economically devastated and made it extremely difficult for many people to have children.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] The Soviet state recognized that banning abortion would not stop the practice because women would continue using the services of private abortionists.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] In rural areas, these were often old women who had no medical training, which made their services very dangerous to women's health.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] In November 1920, the Soviet government legalized abortion in state hospitals.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] The state considered abortion as a temporary necessary evil, which would disappear in the future communist society, which would be able to provide for all the children conceived.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] In 1936, Joseph Stalin placed prohibitions on abortions, which restricted them to medically recommended cases only, in order to increase population growth after the enormous loss of life in World War I and the Russian Civil War.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] In the 1930s, several countries (Poland, Turkey, Denmark, Sweden, Iceland, Mexico) legalized abortion in some special cases (pregnancy from rape, threat to mother's health, fetal malformation).
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] In Japan, abortion was legalized in 1948 by the Eugenic Protection Law, amended in May 1949 to allow abortions for economic reasons.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Abortion was legalized in 1952 in Yugoslavia (on a limited basis), and again in 1955 in the Soviet Union on request.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Some Soviet allies (Poland, Hungary, Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, Romania) legalized abortion in the late 1950s under pressure from the Soviets.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] In the United Kingdom, the Abortion Act of 1967 clarified and prescribed abortions as legal up to 28 weeks (later reduced to 24 weeks).
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Other countries soon followed, including Canada (1969), the United States (1973 in most states, pursuant to *Roe v.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Supreme Court decision which legalized abortion nationwide until 2022), Tunisia and Denmark (1973), Austria (1974), France and Sweden (1975), New Zealand (1977), Italy (1978), the Netherlands (1984), and Belgium (1990).
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] However, these countries vary greatly in the circumstances under which abortion was to be permitted.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] In 1975, the West German Supreme Court struck down a law legalizing abortion, holding that it contradicted the constitution's human rights guarantees.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] In 1976, a law was adopted which enabled abortions up to 12 weeks.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] The other schools hold intermediate positions. ...
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] The penalty prescribed for an illegal abortion varies according to particular circumstances involved.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] The table below lists in chronological order the United Nations member states that have legalized abortion on request in at least some initial part of the pregnancy, or that have fully decriminalized abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] As of 2025, 67 countries have legalized or decriminalized abortion on request.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Where a country has legalized abortion on request, prohibited it, and legalized it again (e.g., former Soviet Union, Romania), only the later year is included.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Countries that result from the merger of states where abortion on request was legal at the moment of unification show the year when it became legal across the whole national territory (e.g., Germany, Vietnam).
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Similarly, countries where not all subnational jurisdictions have legalized abortion on request are not included, leading to the exclusion of Australia, Mexico, and the United Kingdom.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Countries where abortion on request was once legalized nationwide but has since been prohibited in at least part of the country, such as the United States and Poland, are also excluded.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Countries are counted even if they were not yet independent at the time.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] The year refers to when the relevant law or judicial decision came into force, which may be different from the year when it was approved.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] There are no international or multinational treaties that deal directly with abortion but human rights law and international criminal law touch on the issues.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] The Nuremberg Military Tribunal decided the case of *United States v Greifelt and Others* (1948) on the basis that abortion was a crime within its jurisdiction according to the law defining crimes against humanity and thus within its definition of murder and extermination.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] The Catholic Church remains highly influential in Latin America, and opposes the legalisation of abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] The American Convention on Human Rights, which in 2013 had 23 Latin American parties, declares human life as commencing with conception.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] In Latin America, abortion on request is only legal in Cuba (1965), Uruguay (2012), Argentina (2021), Colombia (2022) and in parts of Mexico.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Abortions are completely banned in the Dominican Republic, El Salvador, Honduras and Nicaragua, and only allowed in certain restricted circumstances in most other Latin American nations.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] In the 2010 case of *A, B and C v Ireland*, the European Court of Human Rights found that the European Convention on Human Rights did not include a right to an abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] In the 2016 case of *Mellet v Ireland*, the UN HRC found Ireland's abortion laws violated the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights because Irish law banned abortion in cases of fatal fetal abnormalities.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] While abortions are legal at least under certain conditions in almost all countries, these conditions vary widely.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] According to a United Nations (UN) report with data gathered up to 2019, abortion is allowed in 98% of countries in order to save a woman's life.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Other commonly accepted reasons are preserving physical (72%) or mental health (69%), in cases of rape or incest (61%), and in cases of fetal impairment (61%).
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Performing an abortion because of economic or social reasons is accepted in 37% of countries.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Performing abortion only on the basis of a woman's request is allowed in 34% of countries, including in Canada, most European countries and China.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] The exact scope of each legal ground also varies.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] For example, the laws of some countries cite health risks and fetal impairment as general grounds for abortion and allow a broad interpretation of such terms in practice, while other countries restrict them to a specific list of medical conditions or subcategories.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Many countries that allow abortion have gestational limits for the procedure depending on the reason; with the majority being up to 12 weeks for abortion on request, up to 24 weeks for social, economic, rape, or incest reasons, and more for fetal impairment or threats to the woman's health or life.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] In some countries, additional procedures must be followed before the abortion can be carried out even if the basic grounds for it are met.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] How strictly all of the procedures dictated in the legislation are followed in practice is another matter.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] For example, in the United Kingdom, a Care Quality Commission's report in 2012 found that several NHS clinics were circumventing the law, using forms pre-signed by one doctor, thus allowing abortions to patients who only met with one doctor.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] The table below summarizes the legal grounds for abortion in all United Nations member states and United Nations General Assembly observer states and some countries with limited recognition.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] This table is mostly based on data compiled by the United Nations up to 2019, with some updates, additions and clarifications citing other sources.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] The table below summarizes the legal grounds for abortion in autonomous jurisdictions not included in the previous table.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Legal limits may not be directly comparable.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Limits may be expressed in trimesters, months, weeks of pregnancy (implantation), weeks from fertilization, or weeks from last menstrual period (LMP).
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] According to a report by Women on Waves, approximately 25% of the world's population lives in countries with "highly restrictive abortion laws"—that is, laws which either completely ban abortion, or allow it only to save the mother's life.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] This category includes several countries in Latin America, Africa, Asia and Oceania, as well as Andorra and Malta in Europe.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] El Salvador has some of the strictest abortion laws of any country.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Abortion under all circumstances, including rape, incest, and risk to the mother's health, is illegal.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Women can be criminalized and penalized to up to 40 years in prison after being found guilty of an abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] El Salvador's abortion laws are so severe that miscarriages and stillbirths can sometimes be enough for conviction.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] The Inter-American Court has already ruled that El Salvador was responsible for the death of Manuela, who was sentenced to 30 years in prison in 2008 for aggravated homicide after suffering an obstetric emergency that resulted in her losing her pregnancy.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Controversy over the beginning of pregnancy occurs in different contexts, particularly in a legal context, and is particularly discussed within the abortion debate from the point of measuring the gestational age of the pregnancy.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] Pregnancy can be measured from a number of convenient points, including the day of last menstruation, ovulation, fertilization, implantation and chemical detection.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p01] A common medical way to calculate gestational age is to measure pregnancy from the first day of the last menstrual cycle.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p02] Exceptions in abortion laws occur either in countries where abortion is as a general rule illegal or in countries that have abortion on request with gestational limits.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p02] For example, if a country allows abortion on request until 12 weeks, it may create exceptions to this general gestation limit for later abortions in specific circumstances.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p02] There are a few exceptions commonly found in abortion laws.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p02] Legal domains which do not have abortion on demand will often allow it when the health of the mother is at stake.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p02] Laws allowing abortion in cases of rape or incest often differ.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p02] Wade*, thirteen U.S. states allowed abortion in the case of either rape or incest, but only Mississippi permitted abortion of pregnancies due to rape, and no state permitted it for just incest.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p02] Many countries allow abortion only through the first or second trimester, and some may allow abortion in cases of fetal defects, e.g., Down syndrome, or where the pregnancy is the result of a sexual crime.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p02] Laws in some countries with liberal abortion laws protect access to abortion services.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p02] Such legislation often seeks to guard abortion clinics against obstruction, vandalism, picketing, and other actions, or to protect patients and employees of such facilities from threats and harassment.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p02] Other laws create a perimeter around a facility, known variously as a "buffer zone", "bubble zone", or "access zone", where demonstrations opposing abortion are not permitted.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p02] Protests and other displays are restricted to a certain distance from the building, which varies depending on the law.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p02] Similar zones have also been created to protect the homes of abortion providers and clinic staff.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p02] Bubble zone laws are divided into "fixed" and "floating" categories.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p02] Fixed bubble zone laws apply to the static area around the facility itself, and floating laws to objects in transit, such as people or cars.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p02] On 3 November 2020, an association of 20 Kenyan charities urged the government of Kenya to withdraw from the Geneva Consensus Declaration (GCD), a US-led international accord that sought to limit access to abortion for girls and women around the world.
[src:infertility/abortion-law-p02] GCD was signed by 33 nations, on 22 October 2020.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] When done legally in industrialized societies, induced abortion is one of the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Modern methods use medication or surgery for abortions.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The drug mifepristone (aka RU-486) in combination with prostaglandin appears to be as safe and effective as surgery during the first and second trimesters of pregnancy.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Self-managed medication abortion is highly effective and safe throughout the first trimester.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The most common surgical technique involves dilating the cervix and using a suction device.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Birth control, such as contraceptive pills or intrauterine devices, can be used immediately following an abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] When performed legally and safely on a woman who desires it, an induced abortion does not increase the risk of long-term mental or physical problems.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In contrast, unsafe abortions performed by unskilled individuals, with hazardous equipment, or in unsanitary facilities cause between 22,000 and 44,000 deaths and 6.9 million hospital admissions each year — responsible for between 5% and 13% of maternal deaths, especially in low-income countries.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization states that "access to legal, safe and comprehensive abortion care, including post-abortion care, is essential for the attainment of the highest possible level of sexual and reproductive health".
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Public health data show that making safe abortion legal and accessible reduces maternal deaths.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Around 73 million abortions are performed each year in the world, with about 45% done unsafely.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Abortion rates changed little between 2003 and 2008, before which they decreased for at least two decades as access to family planning and birth control increased.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] As of 2018, 37% of the world's women had access to legal abortions without limits as to reason.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Countries that permit abortions have different limits on how late in pregnancy abortion is allowed.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Abortion rates are similar between countries that restrict abortion and countries that broadly allow it, though this is partly because countries which restrict abortion tend to have higher unintended pregnancy rates.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Since 1973, there has been a global trend towards greater legal access to abortion, but there remains debate with regard to moral, religious, ethical, and legal issues.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Those who oppose abortion often argue that an embryo or fetus is a person with a right to life, and thus equate abortion with murder.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Those who support abortion's legality often argue that it is a woman's reproductive right.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Others favor legal and accessible abortion as a public health measure.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Abortion laws and views of the procedure are different around the world.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In some countries abortion is legal and women have the right to make the choice about abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In some areas, abortion is legal only in specific cases such as rape, incest, fetal defects, poverty, and risk to a woman's health.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Historically, abortions have been attempted using herbal medicines, sharp tools, forceful massage, or other traditional methods.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] An induced abortion is a medical procedure to end a pregnancy.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In present-day English, the term *abortion*, when used without further qualification, generally refers to induced abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] A pregnancy can be intentionally aborted in several ways.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The abortion method depends upon the gestational age of the embryo or fetus, which gains mass as the pregnancy progresses.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Abortion laws, regional availability, and the personal preference of the woman and her doctor may inform the woman's choice of a specific abortion procedure.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Abortions can be characterized as either therapeutic or elective.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] When an abortion is performed for medical reasons, the procedure is referred to as a therapeutic abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] An abortion is referred to as elective or voluntary when it is performed at the request of the woman for non-medical reasons.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Confusion sometimes arises over the term *elective* because "elective surgery" generally refers to all scheduled surgery, whether medically necessary or not.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] About one in five pregnancies worldwide ends with an induced abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Most abortions result from unintended pregnancies.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In the United Kingdom, 1 to 2% of abortions are done because of genetic problems in the fetus.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Miscarriage, also known as spontaneous abortion, is the unintentional expulsion of an embryo or fetus before the 24th week of gestation.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] A pregnancy that ends before 37 weeks of gestation resulting in a live-born infant is a "premature birth" or a "preterm birth".
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] When a fetus dies in utero after viability, or during delivery, it is usually termed "stillborn".
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Premature births and stillbirths are generally not considered to be miscarriages, although usage of these terms can sometimes overlap.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Studies of pregnant women in the US and China have shown that between 40% and 60% of embryos do not progress to birth.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The vast majority of miscarriages occur before the woman is aware that she is pregnant, and many pregnancies spontaneously abort before medical practitioners can detect an embryo.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Between 15% and 30% of known pregnancies end in clinically apparent miscarriage, depending upon the age and health of the pregnant woman.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] 80% of these spontaneous abortions happen in the first trimester.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The most common cause of spontaneous abortion during the first trimester is chromosomal abnormalities of the embryo or fetus, accounting for at least 50% of sampled early pregnancy losses.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Other causes include vascular disease (such as lupus), diabetes, other hormonal problems, infection, and abnormalities of the uterus.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Advancing maternal age and a woman's history of previous spontaneous abortions are the two leading factors associated with a greater risk of spontaneous abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] A spontaneous abortion can also be caused by accidental trauma; intentional trauma or stress to cause miscarriage is considered induced abortion or feticide.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] may determine which abortion methods are practiced.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Medical abortions are those induced by abortifacient pharmaceuticals.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Medical abortion became an alternative method of abortion with the availability of prostaglandin analogs in the 1970s and the antiprogestogen mifepristone (also known as RU-486) in the 1980s.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimens work faster and are more effective at later gestational ages than methotrexate–misoprostol combination regimens, and combination regimens are more effective than misoprostol alone, particularly in the second trimester.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Medical abortion regimens involving mifepristone followed by misoprostol in the cheek between 24 and 48 hours later are effective when performed before 70 days' gestation.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In very early abortions, up to 7 weeks gestation, medical abortion using a mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimen is considered to be more effective than surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration), especially when clinical practice does not include detailed inspection of aspirated tissue.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Early medical abortion regimens using mifepristone, followed 24–48 hours later by buccal or vaginal misoprostol are 98% effective up to 9 weeks gestational age; from 9 to 10 weeks efficacy decreases modestly to 94%.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] If medical abortion fails, surgical abortion must be used to complete the procedure.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Early medical abortions account for the majority of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in Britain, France, Switzerland, United States, and the Nordic countries.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] A 2020 Cochrane Systematic Review concluded that providing women with medications to take home to complete the second stage of the procedure for an early medical abortion results in an effective abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Further research is required to determine if self-administered medical abortion is as safe as provider-administered medical abortion, where a health care professional is present to help manage the medical abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Safely permitting women to self-administer abortion medication has the potential to improve access to abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The review also noted a research gap concerning methods to support women who take medication at home for a self-administered abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Up to 15 weeks' gestation, suction-aspiration or vacuum aspiration are the most common surgical methods of induced abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] *Manual vacuum aspiration* (MVA) consists of removing the fetus or embryo, placenta, and membranes by suction using a manual syringe, while *electric vacuum aspiration* (EVA) uses an electric pump.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Both techniques can be used very early in pregnancy.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] MVA can be used up to 14 weeks but is more often used earlier in the U.S.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] MVA, also known as "mini-suction" and "menstrual extraction", or EVA can be used in very early pregnancy when cervical dilation may not be required.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Dilation and curettage (D&C) refers to opening the cervix (dilation) and removing tissue (curettage) via suction or sharp instruments.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] D&C is a standard gynecological procedure performed for a variety of reasons, including examination of the uterine lining for possible malignancy, investigation of abnormal bleeding, and abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization recommends *sharp curettage* only when suction aspiration is unavailable.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Dilation and evacuation (D&E), used after 12 to 16 weeks, consists of opening the cervix and removing pregnancy tissue and fetal parts with suction and forceps.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] D&E is performed vaginally and does not require an incision.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Intact dilation and extraction (D&X) refers to a variant of D&E sometimes used after 18 to 20 weeks when removal of an intact fetus improves surgical safety or for other reasons.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Abortion may also be performed surgically by hysterotomy or gravid hysterectomy.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy abortion is a procedure similar to a caesarean section and is performed under general anesthesia.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] It requires a smaller incision than a caesarean section and can be used during later stages of pregnancy.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Gravid hysterectomy refers to removal of the whole uterus while still containing the pregnancy.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy and hysterectomy are associated with much higher rates of maternal morbidity and mortality than D&E or induction abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] First trimester procedures can generally be performed using local anesthesia, while second trimester methods may require deep sedation or general anesthesia.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In places lacking the necessary medical skill for dilation and extraction, or when preferred by practitioners, an abortion can be induced by first inducing labor and then inducing fetal demise if necessary.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] This is sometimes called "induced miscarriage".
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] This procedure may be performed from 13 weeks gestation to the third trimester.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Although it is very uncommon in the United States, more than 80% of induced abortions throughout the second trimester are labor-induced abortions in Sweden and other nearby countries.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Only limited data are available comparing labor-induced abortion with the dilation and extraction method.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Unlike D&E, labor-induced abortions after 18 weeks may be complicated by the occurrence of brief fetal survival, which may be legally characterized as live birth.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] For this reason, labor-induced abortion is legally risky in the United States.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Historically, a number of herbs reputed to possess abortifacient properties have been used in folk medicine.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Such herbs include tansy, pennyroyal, black cohosh, and the now-extinct silphium.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In 1978, one woman in Colorado died and another developed organ damage when they attempted to terminate their pregnancies by taking pennyroyal oil.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Because the indiscriminant use of herbs as abortifacients can cause serious—even lethal—side effects, such as multiple organ failure, such use is not recommended by physicians.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Abortion is sometimes attempted by causing trauma to the abdomen.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The degree of force, if severe, can cause serious internal injuries without necessarily succeeding in inducing miscarriage.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In Southeast Asia, there is an ancient tradition of attempting abortion through forceful abdominal massage.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] One of the bas reliefs decorating the temple of Angkor Wat in Cambodia depicts a demon performing such an abortion upon a woman who had been sent to the underworld.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Reported methods of unsafe, self-induced abortion include misuse of misoprostol and insertion of non-surgical implements such as knitting needles and clothes hangers into the uterus.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] These and other methods to terminate pregnancy may be called "induced miscarriage".
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Such methods are rarely used in countries where surgical abortion is legal and available.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The health risks of abortion depend principally on how, and under what conditions, the procedure is performed.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) defines unsafe abortions as a procedure for terminating an unintended pregnancy carried out either by persons lacking the necessary skills or in an environment that does not conform to minimal medical standards, or both.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Legal abortions performed in the developed world are among the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] According to a 2012 study in *Obstetrics & Gynecology*, in the United States the risk of maternal mortality is 14 times lower after induced abortion than after childbirth.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The CDC estimated in 2019 that US pregnancy-related mortality was 17.2 maternal deaths per 100,000 live births, while the US abortion mortality rate was 0.43 maternal deaths per 100,000 procedures.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In the UK, guidelines of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists state that "Women should be advised that abortion is generally safer than continuing a pregnancy to term." Worldwide, on average, abortion is safer than carrying a pregnancy to term.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In the US from 2000 to 2009, abortion had a mortality rate lower than plastic surgery, lower or similar to running a marathon, and about equivalent to traveling 760 miles (1,220 km) in a passenger car.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Outpatient abortion is as safe from 64 to 70 days' gestation as it before 63 days.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] A 2019 study indicated that five years after seeking abortion services, women who gave birth after being denied an abortion reported worse health than women who had either first or second trimester abortions.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] There is little difference in terms of safety and efficacy between medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol and surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration) in early first trimester abortions up to 10 weeks gestation.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Medical abortion using the prostaglandin analog misoprostol alone is less effective and more painful than medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol or surgical abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Vacuum aspiration in the first trimester is the safest method of surgical abortion, and can be performed in a primary care office, abortion clinic, or hospital.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Complications, which are rare, can include uterine perforation, pelvic infection, and retained products of conception requiring a second procedure to evacuate.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Infections account for one-third of abortion-related deaths in the United States.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The rate of complications of vacuum aspiration abortion in the first trimester is similar regardless of whether the procedure is performed in a hospital, surgical center, or office.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Preventive antibiotics (such as doxycycline or metronidazole) are typically given before abortion procedures, as they are believed to substantially reduce the risk of postoperative uterine infection; however, antibiotics are not routinely given with abortion pills.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The rate of failed procedures does not appear to vary significantly depending on whether the abortion is performed by a doctor or a mid-level practitioner.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Complications after second trimester abortion are similar to those after first trimester abortion, and depend somewhat on the method chosen.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The risk of death from abortion approaches roughly half the risk of death from childbirth the farther along a woman is in pregnancy; from one in a million before 9 weeks gestation to nearly one in ten thousand at 21 weeks or more (as measured from the last menstrual period).
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] It appears that having had a prior surgical uterine evacuation (whether because of induced abortion or treatment of miscarriage) correlates with a small increase in the risk of preterm birth in future pregnancies.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The studies supporting this did not control for factors not related to abortion or miscarriage, and hence the causes of this correlation have not been determined, although multiple possibilities have been suggested.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Current evidence finds no relationship between most induced abortions and mental health problems other than those expected for any unwanted pregnancy.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Some older reviews concluded that abortion was associated with an increased risk of psychological problems; however, later reviews of the medical literature found that previous reviews did not use an appropriate control group.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] When a control group is utilized, receiving abortion is not associated with adverse psychological outcomes.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] However, women seeking abortion who are denied access to abortion have an increase in anxiety after the denial.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Although some studies show negative mental-health outcomes in women who choose abortions after the first trimester because of fetal abnormalities, more rigorous research would be needed to show this conclusively.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Some proposed negative psychological effects of abortion have been referred to by anti-abortion advocates as a separate condition called "post-abortion syndrome", but this is not recognized by medical or psychological professionals in the United States.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] A 2020 long term-study among US women found that about 99% of women felt that they made the right decision five years after they had an abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Relief was the primary emotion with few women feeling sadness or guilt.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Social stigma was a main factor predicting negative emotions and regret years later.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Some purported risks of abortion are promoted primarily by anti-abortion groups, but lack scientific support.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] For example, the question of a link between induced abortion and breast cancer has been investigated extensively.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Major medical and scientific bodies (including the WHO, National Cancer Institute, American Cancer Society, Royal College of OBGYN and American Congress of OBGYN) have concluded that abortion does not cause breast cancer.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In the past even illegality has not automatically meant that the abortions were unsafe.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] A 1940s American physician spoke of his pride in having performed 13,844 illegal abortions without any fatalities.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In 1870s New York City, the abortionist/midwife Madame Restell (Anna Trow Lohman) is said to have lost very few women among her more than 100,000 patients—a lower mortality rate than the childbirth mortality rate at the time.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In 1936, obstetrics and gynecology professor Frederick J.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Women seeking an abortion may use unsafe methods, especially when abortion is legally restricted.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] They may attempt self-induced abortion or seek the help of a person without proper medical training or facilities.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] This can lead to severe complications, such as incomplete abortion, sepsis, hemorrhage, and damage to internal organs.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are a major cause of injury and death among women worldwide.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Although data are imprecise, it is estimated that approximately 20 million unsafe abortions are performed annually, with 97% taking place in developing countries.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are believed to result in millions of injuries.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Estimates of deaths vary according to methodology, and have ranged from 37,000 to 70,000 in the past decade; deaths from unsafe abortion account for around 13% of all maternal deaths.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization believes that mortality has fallen since the 1990s.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] To reduce the number of unsafe abortions, public health organizations have generally advocated emphasizing the legalization of abortion, training of medical personnel, and ensuring access to reproductive-health services.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] A major factor in whether abortions are performed safely or not is the legal standing of abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Countries with restrictive abortion laws have higher rates of unsafe abortion and similar overall abortion rates compared to countries where abortion is legal and available.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] For example, the 1996 legalization of abortion in South Africa led to an immediate reduction in abortion-related complications, with abortion-related deaths dropping by more than 90%.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Similar reductions in maternal mortality have been observed after other countries have liberalized their abortion laws, such as Romania and Nepal.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] A 2011 study concluded that in the United States, some state-level anti-abortion laws are correlated with lower rates of abortion in that state.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The analysis, however, did not take into account travel to other states without such laws to obtain an abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In addition, a lack of access to effective contraception contributes to unsafe abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] It has been estimated that the incidence of unsafe abortion could be reduced by up to 75% (from 20 million to 5 million annually) if modern family planning and maternal health services were readily available globally.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Rates of such abortions may be difficult to measure because they can be reported variously as miscarriage, "induced miscarriage", "menstrual regulation", "mini-abortion", and "regulation of a delayed/suspended menstruation".
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Forty percent of the world's women are able to access therapeutic and elective abortions within gestational limits, while an additional 35 percent have access to legal abortion if they meet certain physical, mental, or socioeconomic criteria.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] While maternal mortality seldom results from safe abortions, unsafe abortions result in 70,000 deaths and 5 million disabilities per year.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Complications of unsafe abortion account for approximately an eighth of maternal mortalities worldwide, though this varies by region.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Secondary infertility caused by an unsafe abortion affects an estimated 24 million women.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The rate of unsafe abortions has increased from 44% to 49% between 1995 and 2008.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Health education, access to family planning, and improvements in health care during and after abortion have been proposed to address consequences of unsafe abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In many places, where abortion is illegal or carries a heavy social stigma, medical reporting of abortion is not reliable.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] For this reason, estimates of the incidence of abortion must be made without determining certainty related to standard error.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The number of abortions performed worldwide was characterized as stable in the early 2000s, with 41.6 million having been performed in 2003 and 43.8 million having been performed in 2008.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The abortion rate worldwide was 28 per 1000 women per year, though it was 24 per 1000 women per year for developed countries and 29 per 1000 women per year for developing countries.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The same 2012 study indicated that in 2008, the estimated abortion percentage of known pregnancies was at 21% worldwide, with 26% in developed countries and 20% in developing countries.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] On average, the incidence of abortion is similar in countries with restrictive abortion laws and those with more liberal access to abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Restrictive abortion laws are associated with increases in the percentage of abortions performed unsafely.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The rate of legal, induced abortion varies extensively worldwide.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] According to the report of employees of Guttmacher Institute it ranged from 7 per 1000 women per year (Germany and Switzerland) to 30 per 1000 women per year (Estonia) in countries with complete statistics in 2008.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The proportion of pregnancies that ended in induced abortion ranged from about 10% (Israel, the Netherlands and Switzerland) to 30% (Estonia) in the same group, though it might be as high as 36% in Hungary and Romania, whose statistics were deemed incomplete.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] An American study in 2002 concluded that about half of women having abortions were using a form of contraception at the time of becoming pregnant.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Inconsistent use was reported by half of those using condoms and three-quarters of those using the birth control pill; 42% of those using condoms reported failure through slipping or breakage.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Of the other half of women, who were not using contraception at the time of becoming pregnant, the vast majority had used contraception at some point in the past, indicating some level of dissatisfaction with the contraceptive options available to them.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Indeed, 32% of these contraceptive nonusers cited concerns about contraceptive methods as their reason for nonuse, and a more recent study found similar results.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Taken together, these statistics suggest that new contraceptive methods, such as non-hormonal contraceptives or male contraceptives, could reduce unintended pregnancy and abortion rates.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute has found that "most abortions in the United States are obtained by minority women" because minority women "have much higher rates of unintended pregnancy".
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] in England and Wales during 2019 (left).
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Abortion in the United States by gestational age, 2016 (right).
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Abortion rates vary depending on the stage of pregnancy and the method practiced.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] 91% of these were classified as having been done by "curettage" (suction-aspiration, dilation and curettage, dilation and evacuation), 8% by "medical" means (mifepristone), >1% by "intrauterine instillation" (saline or prostaglandin), and 1% by "other" (including hysterotomy and hysterectomy).
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] According to the CDC, due to data collection difficulties the data must be viewed as tentative and some fetal deaths reported beyond 20 weeks may be natural deaths erroneously classified as abortions if the removal of the dead fetus is accomplished by the same procedure as an induced abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute estimated there were 2,200 intact dilation and extraction procedures in the US during 2000; this accounts for <0.2% of the total number of abortions performed that year.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Similarly, in England and Wales in 2006, 89% of terminations occurred at or under 12 weeks, 9% between 13 and 19 weeks, and 2% at or over 20 weeks.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] 64% of those reported were by vacuum aspiration, 6% by D&E, and 30% were medical.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] There are more second trimester abortions in developing countries such as China, India and Vietnam than in developed countries.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] There are both medical and non-medical reasons to have an abortion later in pregnancy (after 20 weeks).
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] A study was conducted from 2008 to 2010 at the University of California San Francisco where more than 440 women were asked about why they experienced delays in obtaining abortion care, if there were any.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] This study found that almost half of individuals who obtained an abortion after 20 weeks did not suspect that they were pregnant until later in their pregnancy.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Other barriers to abortion care found in the study included lack of information about where to access an abortion, difficulties with transportation, lack of insurance coverage, and inability to pay for the abortion procedure.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Medical reasons for seeking an abortion later in pregnancy include fetal anomalies and health risk to the pregnant person.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] There are prenatal tests that can diagnose Down Syndrome or cystic fibrosis as early as 10 weeks into gestation, but structural fetal anomalies are often detected much later in pregnancy.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] A proportion of structural fetal anomalies are lethal, which means that the fetus will almost certainly die before or shortly after birth.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Life-threatening conditions may also develop later in pregnancy, such as early severe preeclampsia, newly diagnosed cancer in need of urgent treatment, and intrauterine infection (chorioamnionitis), which often occurs along with premature rupture of the amniotic sac (PPROM).
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] If serious medical conditions such as these arise before the fetus is viable, the person carrying the pregnancy may pursue an abortion to preserve their own health.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The reasons why women have abortions are diverse and vary across the world.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Some of the reasons may include an inability to afford a child, domestic violence, lack of support, feeling they are too young, and the wish to complete education or advance a career.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Additional reasons include not being able or willing to raise a child conceived as a result of rape or incest.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Some abortions are undergone as the result of societal pressures.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] These factors can sometimes result in compulsory abortion or sex-selective abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In cultures where there is a preference for male children, some women have sex selective abortions, which have partially replaced the earlier practice of female infanticide.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Some abortions are performed due to concerns over maternal health.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In 1990s, women cited maternal health as their main motivating factor in about a third of abortions in three of 27 countries analyzed.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In seven additional countries, about 7% of abortions were maternal health related.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In the U.S., the Supreme Court decisions in *Roe v.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Bolton*: "ruled that the state's interest in the life of the fetus became compelling only at the point of viability, defined as the point at which the fetus can survive independently of its mother.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Even after the point of viability, the state cannot favor the life of the fetus over the life or health of the pregnant woman.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Under the right of privacy, physicians must be free to use their "medical judgment for the preservation of the life or health of the mother".
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] On the same day that the Court decided Roe, it also decided Doe v.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Bolton, in which the Court defined health very broadly: "The medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The rate of cancer during pregnancy is 0.02–1%, and in many cases, cancer of the mother leads to consideration of abortion to protect the life of the mother, or in response to the potential damage that may occur to the fetus during treatment.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] This is particularly true for cervical cancer, the most common type of which occurs in 1 of every 2,000–13,000 pregnancies, for which initiation of treatment "cannot co-exist with preservation of fetal life (unless neoadjuvant chemotherapy is chosen)".
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Very early stage cervical cancers (I and IIa) may be treated by radical hysterectomy and pelvic lymph node dissection, radiation therapy, or both, while later stages are treated by radiotherapy.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Chemotherapy may be used simultaneously.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Treatment of breast cancer during pregnancy also involves fetal considerations, because lumpectomy is discouraged in favor of modified radical mastectomy unless late-term pregnancy allows follow-up radiation therapy to be administered after the birth.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Exposure to a single chemotherapy drug is estimated to cause a 7.5–17% risk of teratogenic effects on the fetus, with higher risks for multiple drug treatments.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Treatment with more than 40 Gy of radiation usually causes spontaneous abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Exposure to much lower doses during the first trimester, especially 8 to 15 weeks of development, can cause intellectual disability or microcephaly, and exposure at this or subsequent stages can cause reduced intrauterine growth and birth weight.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Exposures above 0.005–0.025 Gy cause a dose-dependent reduction in IQ.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] It is possible to greatly reduce exposure to radiation with abdominal shielding, depending on how far the area to be irradiated is from the fetus.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The process of birth itself may also put the mother at risk.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Congenital disorders, revealed by prenatal screening, motivate some women to seek abortions.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Health outcomes of preterm births include a significant probability of long-term neurodevelopmental impairment before gestational age of 29 weeks, with a higher probability with decreasing gestational age.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In the United States, public opinion shifted after television personality Sherri Finkbine's was exposed to thalidomide, a teratogen, in her fifth month of pregnancy.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Unable to obtain a legal abortion in the United States, Finkbine traveled to Sweden.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] From 1962 to 1965, an outbreak of German measles left 15,000 babies with severe birth defects.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In 1967, the American Medical Association publicly supported liberalization of abortion laws.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] A National Opinion Research Center poll in 1965 showed 73% supported abortion when the mother's life was at risk, 57% when birth defects were present and 59% for pregnancies resulting from rape or incest.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Since ancient times, abortions have been done using a number of methods, including herbal medicines acting as abortifacients, sharp tools through the use of force, or through other traditional medicine methods.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Induced abortion has a long history and can be traced back to civilizations as varied as ancient China (abortifacient knowledge is often attributed to the mythological ruler Shennong), ancient India since its Vedic age, ancient Egypt with its Ebers Papyrus (c.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] 1550 BCE), and the Roman Empire in the time of Juvenal (c.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] One of the earliest known artistic representations of abortion is in a bas relief at Angkor Wat (c.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Found in a series of friezes that represent judgment after death in Hindu and Buddhist culture, it depicts the technique of abdominal abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In *Politics* (350 BCE), Aristotle condemned infanticide as a means of population control.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] He preferred abortion in such cases, with the restriction that it "must be practised on it before it has developed sensation and life; for the line between lawful and unlawful abortion will be marked by the fact of having sensation and being alive".
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Abortion has been a fairly common practice, and was not always illegal or controversial until the 19th century.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In Europe and North America, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century; the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Other medical practitioners in addition to some physicians advertised their services, and they were not widely regulated until the 19th century when the practice, sometimes called *restellism*, was banned in both the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Some 19th-century physicians, argued for anti-abortion laws on racist and misogynist as well as moral grounds.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Church groups were also highly influential in anti-abortion movements, and religious groups more so since the 20th century.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Some of the early anti-abortion laws punished only the doctor or abortionist, and while women could be criminally tried for a self-induced abortion, they were rarely prosecuted in general.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Some maintain that in the 19th century early abortions under the hygienic conditions in which midwives usually worked were relatively safe.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Several scholars argue that, despite improved medical procedures, the period from the 1930s until the 1970s saw more zealous enforcement of anti-abortion laws, alongside an increasing control of abortion providers by organized crime.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In 1920, Soviet Russia became the first country to legalize abortion after Lenin insisted that no woman be forced to give birth.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Abortion was then legalized in some form in Iceland (1935), Sweden (1938), Nazi Germany (1935) and Japan (1948) Beginning in the second half of the 20th century, abortion was legalized in a greater number of countries.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In the Catholic Church, opinion was divided on how serious abortion was in comparison with such acts as contraception and oral or anal sex.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The Catholic Church did not begin vigorously opposing abortion until the 19th century.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] As early as ~100 CE, the *Didache* taught that abortion was sinful.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Several historians argue that prior to the 19th century most Catholic authors did not regard termination of pregnancy before quickening or ensoulment as an abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] 1585–1590) was the first Pope to institute a Church policy labeling all abortion as homicide and condemning abortion regardless of the stage of pregnancy.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Sixtus V's pronouncement was reversed in 1591 by Pope Gregory XIV.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In the recodification of 1917 Code of Canon Law, *Apostolicae Sedis* was strengthened, in part to remove a possible reading that excluded excommunication of the mother.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Statements made in the *Catechism of the Catholic Church*, the codified summary of the Church's teachings, considers abortion from the moment of conception as homicide and called for the end of legal abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Denominations that support abortion rights with some limits include the United Methodist Church, Episcopal Church, Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and Presbyterian Church USA.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] A 2014 Guttmacher survey of abortion patients in the United States found that many reported a religious affiliation: 24% were Catholic while 30% were Protestant.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] A 1995 survey reported that Catholic women are as likely as the general population to terminate a pregnancy, Protestants are less likely to do so, and evangelical Christians are the least likely to do so.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] A 2019 Pew Research Center study found that most Christian denominations were against overturning *Roe v.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Wade,* which in the United States legalized abortion, at around 70%, except White Evangelicals at 35%.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In Judaism, the fetus is not considered to have a human soul until it is safely outside of the woman, is viable, and has taken its first breath.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] The fetus is considered valuable property of the woman and not a human life while in the womb (Exodus 21:22-23).
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] While Judaism encourages people to be fruitful and multiply by having children, abortion is allowed and is deemed necessary when a pregnant woman's life is in danger.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Several religions, including Judaism, which disagree that human life begins at conception, support the legality of abortion on religious freedom grounds.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] In Islam, abortion is traditionally permitted until a point in time when Muslims believe the soul enters the fetus, considered by various theologians to be at conception, 40 days after conception, 120 days after conception, or at quickening.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Abortion is largely heavily restricted or forbidden in areas of high Islamic faith such as the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Hindu views on abortion are diverse and lack a single authoritative position, shaped by principles like ahimsa (non-violence), karma, and reincarnation, which typically regard it as morally wrong for interrupting the soul's cycle.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Scriptures often equate abortion to grave sins, with the fetus considered ensouled from conception or early gestation.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] However, it may be ethically permissible to save the mother's life or in cases of severe fetal abnormalities, prioritizing lesser harm.
[src:infertility/abortion-p01] Modern opinions differ regionally: In India, a majority view abortion as generally illegal, while in the US, most Hindus support legal access in all or most cases.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Induced abortion has long been the source of considerable debate.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Ethical, moral, philosophical, biological, religious and legal issues surrounding abortion are related to value systems.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Opinions of abortion may be about fetal rights, governmental authority, and women's rights.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] In both public and private debate, arguments presented in favor of or against abortion access focus on either the moral permissibility of an induced abortion, or the justification of laws permitting or restricting abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] The World Medical Association Declaration on Therapeutic Abortion notes, "circumstances bringing the interests of a mother into conflict with the interests of her unborn child create a dilemma and raise the question as to whether or not the pregnancy should be deliberately terminated".
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Abortion debates, especially pertaining to abortion laws, are often spearheaded by groups advocating one of these two positions.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Groups who favor greater legal restrictions on abortion, including complete prohibition, most often describe themselves as "pro-life" while groups who are against such legal restrictions describe themselves as "pro-choice".
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] The median voters stance on abortion varies by jurisdiction and can result in swing votes.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Current laws pertaining to abortion are diverse.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Religious, moral, and cultural factors continue to influence abortion laws throughout the world.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] The right to life, the right to liberty, the right to security of person, and the right to reproductive health are major issues of human rights that sometimes constitute the basis for the existence or absence of abortion laws.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] In jurisdictions where abortion is legal, certain requirements must often be met before a woman may obtain a legal abortion (an abortion performed without the woman's consent is considered feticide and is generally illegal).
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] These requirements usually depend on the age of the fetus, often using a trimester-based system to regulate the window of legality, or as in the U.S., on a doctor's evaluation of the fetus' viability.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Some jurisdictions require a waiting period before the procedure, prescribe the distribution of information on fetal development, or require that parents be contacted if their minor daughter requests an abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Many restrictions are waived in emergency situations.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] China, which has ended their one-child policy, and now has a three-child policy, has at times incorporated mandatory abortions as part of their population control strategy.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Other jurisdictions ban abortion almost entirely.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Many, but not all, of these allow legal abortions in a variety of circumstances.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] These circumstances vary based on jurisdiction, but may include whether the pregnancy is a result of rape or incest, the fetus' development is impaired, the woman's physical or mental well-being is endangered, or socioeconomic considerations make childbirth a hardship.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] In countries where abortion is banned entirely, such as Nicaragua, medical authorities have recorded rises in maternal death directly and indirectly due to pregnancy as well as deaths due to doctors' fears of prosecution if they treat other gynecological emergencies.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Some countries, such as Bangladesh, that nominally ban abortion, may also support clinics that perform abortions under the guise of menstrual hygiene.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] This is also a terminology in traditional medicine.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] In places where abortion is illegal or carries heavy social stigma, pregnant women may engage in medical tourism and travel to countries where they can terminate their pregnancies.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Women on Waves has provided medication abortion and education on a ship in international waters off the coast of countries with restrictive abortion laws.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Women without the means to travel can resort to providers of illegal abortions or attempt to perform an abortion by themselves.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Sonography and amniocentesis allow parents to determine sex before childbirth.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] The development of this technology has led to sex-selective abortion, or the termination of a fetus based on its sex.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] The selective termination of a female fetus is most common.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Sex-selective abortion is partially responsible for the noticeable disparities between the birth rates of male and female children in some countries.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] The preference for male children is reported in many areas of Asia, and abortion used to limit female births has been reported in Taiwan, South Korea, India, and China.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] This deviation from the standard birth rates of males and females occurs despite the fact that the country in question may have officially banned sex-selective abortion or even sex-screening.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Many countries have taken legislative steps to reduce the incidence of sex-selective abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] At the International Conference on Population and Development in 1994 over 180 states agreed to eliminate "all forms of discrimination against the girl child and the root causes of son preference", conditions also condemned by a PACE resolution in 2011.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] On the other hand, measures to reduce gender inequality can reduce the prevalence of such abortions without attendant negative consequences.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Abortion providers and facilities have been subjected to violence, including murder, assault, arson, and bombing.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Some scholars consider anti-abortion violence to be within the definition of terrorism, a view shared by some governments.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] In the U.S. and Canada, over 8,000 incidents of violence, trespassing, and death threats have been recorded by providers since 1977, including over 200 bombings/arsons and hundreds of assaults.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Abortion clinics have also been targeted by acid attacks, invasions, and vandalism The majority of abortion opponents have not been involved in violent acts.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Physicians and other abortion clinic staff have been murdered by abortion opponents.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] In the United States, at least four physicians have been murdered in connection with their work at abortion clinics, including David Gunn (1993), John Britton (1994), Barnett Slepian (1998), and George Tiller (2009).
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] In Canada, gynecologist Garson Romalis survived murder attempts in both 1994 and 2000.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Besides physicians, killings have targeted other clinic staff, such as John Salvi's 1994 murder of two receptionists in Massachusetts clinic and Peter Knight's 2001 murder of a security guard in a Melbourne clinic.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Notable perpetrators of anti-abortion violence include Eric Rudolph, Scott Roeder, Shelley Shannon, and Paul Hill, the first person to be executed in the United States for murdering an abortion provider.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Some countries have laws to protecting access to abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Such laws prevent abortion opponents from interfering with access to legal abortion services.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] For example, the American Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act bars the use of threats or violence to interfere with abortion access.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Abortion access laws may also establish safe access zones around abortion clinics, with limits on protests and enhanced penalties for anti-abortion violence.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Psychological pressure may also be used to limit abortion access.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Some protestors record women entering clinics on camera.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Spontaneous abortion occurs in various animals.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] For example, in sheep it may be caused by stress or physical exertion, such as crowding through doors or being chased by dogs.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] In cows, abortion may be caused by contagious disease, such as brucellosis or *Campylobacter*, but can often be controlled by vaccination.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Eating pine needles can also induce abortions in cows.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Several plants, including broomweed, skunk cabbage, poison hemlock, and tree tobacco, are known to cause fetal deformities and abortion in cattle, and in sheep and goats.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] In horses, a fetus may be aborted or resorbed if it has lethal white syndrome.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Foal embryos that are homozygous for the dominant white gene (WW) are theorized to also be aborted or resorbed before birth.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] In many species of sharks and rays, stress-induced abortions occur frequently upon capture.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Viral infection can cause abortion in dogs.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Cats can experience spontaneous abortion for many reasons, including hormonal imbalance.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] A combined abortion and spaying are performed on pregnant cats, especially in trap–neuter–return programs, to prevent unwanted kittens from being born.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Female rodents may terminate a pregnancy when exposed to the smell of a male not responsible for the pregnancy, known as the Bruce effect.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Abortion may also be induced in animals, in the context of animal husbandry.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] For example, abortion may be induced in mares that have been mated improperly, or that have been purchased by owners who did not realize the mares were pregnant, or that are pregnant with twin foals.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Feticide can occur in horses and zebras due to male harassment of pregnant mares or forced copulation, although the frequency in the wild has been questioned.
[src:infertility/abortion-p02] Male gray langur monkeys may attack females following male takeover, causing miscarriage.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The issue of induced abortion remains divisive in public life, with recurring arguments to liberalize or restrict access to legal abortion services.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Some abortion-rights supporters are divided as to the types of abortion services that should be available under different circumstances, including periods in the pregnancy such as late term abortions, in which access may or may not be restricted.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Many of the terms used in the debate are political framing terms used to validate one's stance while invalidating the opposition.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] For example, the labels pro-choice and pro-life imply endorsement of widely held values such as liberty and freedom, while suggesting that the opposition must be "anti-choice" or "anti-life".
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] These views do not always align along a strict binary.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In one poll conducted by the Public Religion Research Institute, the ambiguity of the terms led 70% of Americans to identify as 'pro-choice,' while nearly two-thirds simultaneously identified as "pro-life".
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] It was found that, in polling, respondents would label themselves differently when given specific details about the circumstances around an abortion including factors such as rape, incest, viability of the fetus, and survivability of the mother.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The Associated Press favors the terms "abortion rights" and "anti-abortion" instead.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion practices date back to 1550 BCE, based on the findings of practices recorded on documents.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion has been an active practice since Egyptian medicine.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Centuries later, abortion was a topic taken up by feminism.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Mohr, there was an earlier acceptance of abortion, and opposition to abortion, including anti-abortion laws, only came into being in the 19th century.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] It was not always a crime and was generally not illegal until quickening, which occurred between the fourth and sixth months of pregnancy.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In the 19th century, the medical profession was generally opposed to abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Mohr argues that the opposition arose due to competition between men with medical degrees and women without one, such as Madame Drunette.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The practice of abortion was one of the first medical specialities, and was practiced by unlicensed people; well-off people had abortions and paid well.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The press played a key role in rallying support for anti-abortion laws.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The ideas of the legalization of abortion in the late 19th century were often opposed by feminists, seeing it as a means of relieving men of responsibility.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In *The Revolution*, which was an official published newspaper of women's rights that went out weekly, operated by Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Anthony, an anonymous contributor signing "A" wrote in 1869 about the subject, arguing that instead of merely attempting to pass a law against abortion, the root cause must also be addressed.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] *The Revolution* newspaper highly impacted the women's rights movement, and for the first time, it seemed like women's voices were being heard through the proclamations of these unacknowledged subjects regarding women and their everyday rights and safety as citizens.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The writer wrote that simply passing an anti-abortion law would "be only mowing off the top of the noxious weed, while the root remains. ...
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] No matter what the motive, love of ease, or a desire to save from suffering the unborn innocent, the woman is awfully guilty who commits the deed.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Between 1900 and 1965, there were not any anti-abortion movements or rallies because states had already passed a law banning abortions at all levels, including prescriptions and procedures.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The only exception for a woman to get an abortion without fear of legal retribution was if a licensed physician determined the abortion would protect the mother's life.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Physicians who provide abortions and women who have abortions were constantly harassed by courts and prosecutors.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In the 1960s, some states began to request changes with the abortion law.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In 1959, a group of experts set up a model enactment that supported the advancement of the abortion laws.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] These experts suggested that the abortion laws should provide exemptions for women that were sexually assaulted or for a baby that may not have a good quality of life.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The abortion-rights movement became a controversial topic in the United States regarding abortion and reproduction.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The movement towards the liberalization of abortion law emerged in the 1920s and 1930s in the context of the victories that had been recently won in the area of birth control.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Campaigners including Marie Stopes in England and Margaret Sanger in the US had succeeded in bringing the issue into the open, and birth control clinics were established that offered family planning advice and contraceptive methods to women in need.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Birth control is a method of pregnancy prevention through controlled contraception.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In 1929, the Infant Life Preservation Act was passed in the United Kingdom, which amended the law (Offences against the Person Act 1861) so that an abortion carried out in good faith, for the sole purpose of preserving the life of the mother, would not be an offense.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Many citizens had mixed opinions on this, but ultimately started protesting this as child destruction.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Child destruction was known as taking the life of a viable unborn child during a pregnancy or at birth, before it is independent of its mother.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] If there is an intent of death and no good faith is carried out in the process in order to protect the mother's livelihood, the offense carries a maximum punishment of life imprisonment.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The Infant Life Preservation Act defines the difference between murder and abortion-the causing of a miscarriage.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Stella Browne was a leading birth control campaigner, who increasingly began to venture into the more contentious issue of abortion in the 1930s.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Browne's beliefs were heavily influenced by the work of Havelock Ellis, Edward Carpenter and other sexologists.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] She came to strongly believe that working women should have the choice to become pregnant and to terminate their pregnancy while they worked in the horrible circumstances surrounding a pregnant woman who was still required to do hard labor during her pregnancy.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In this case she argued that doctors should give free information about birth control to women that wanted to know about it.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] This would give women agency over their own circumstances and allow them to decide whether they wanted to be mothers or not.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] These talks urged women to take matters of their sexuality and their health into their own hands.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] She became increasingly interested in her view of the woman's right to terminate their pregnancies, and in 1929, she brought forward her lecture "The Right to Abortion" in front of the World Sexual Reform Congress in London.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In 1931, Browne began to develop her argument for women's right to decide to have an abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] She again began touring, giving lectures on abortion and the negative consequences that followed if women were unable to terminate pregnancies of their own choosing such as: suicide, injury, permanent invalidism, madness and blood-poisoning.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] On February 17, 1936, Janet Chance, Alice Jenkins and Joan Malleson established the Abortion Law Reform Association as the first advocacy organization for abortion liberalization.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The association promoted access to abortion in the United Kingdom and campaigned for the elimination of legal obstacles.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In its first year ALRA recruited 35 members, and by 1939 had almost 400 members.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The ALRA was very active between 1936 and 1939 sending speakers around the country to talk about Labour and Equal Citizenship and attempted, though most often unsuccessfully, to have letters and articles published in newspapers.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] They became the most popular when a member of the ALRA's Medico-Legal Committee received the case of a fourteen-year-old girl who had been raped, and received a termination of this pregnancy from Dr.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Joan Malleson, a progenitor of the ALRA.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In 1938, Joan Malleson precipitated one of the most influential cases in British abortion law when she referred a pregnant fourteen-year old rape survivor to gynaecologist Aleck Bourne.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] He performed an abortion, then illegal, and was put on trial on charges of procuring abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Bourne was eventually acquitted in *R v.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Bourne*as his actions were "...an example of disinterested conduct in consonance with the highest traditions of the profession".
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] This court case set a precedent that doctors could not be prosecuted for performing an abortion in cases where pregnancy would probably cause "mental and physical wreck".
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The Abortion Law Reform Association continued its campaigning after the Second World War, and this, combined with broad social changes brought the issue of abortion back into the political arena in the 1960s.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In America an abortion reform movement emerged in the 1960s.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In 1964, Gerri Santoro of Connecticut died trying to obtain an illegal abortion and her photo became the symbol of the abortion rights movement.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Some women's rights activist groups developed their own skills to provide abortions to women who could not obtain them elsewhere.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] As an example, in Chicago, a group known as "Jane" operated a floating abortion clinic throughout much of the 1960s.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Women seeking the procedure would call a designated number and be given instructions on how to find "Jane".
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In the late 1960s, a number of organizations were formed to mobilize opinion both against and for the legalization of abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The forerunner of the NARAL Pro-Choice America was formed in 1969 to oppose restrictions on abortion and expand access to abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In late 1973, NARAL became the National Abortion Rights Action League.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The landmark judicial ruling of the Supreme Court in *Roe v.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Wade* ruled that a Texas statute forbidding abortion except when necessary to save the life of the mother was unconstitutional.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] This was back in 1970, where Jane Roe, (which was actually a fictional name used in the court documents in order to protect the plaintiff's identity), had filed a lawsuit against Henry Wade.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] He was the district attorney of Dallas County in Texas, where Jane Roe resided.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] She was challenging a Texas law making abortion illegal except by a doctor's orders to save a woman's life.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The Court arrived at its decision by concluding that the issue of abortion and abortion rights falls under the right to privacy.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The Court held that a right to privacy existed and included the right to have an abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The court found that a mother had a right to abortion until viability, a point to be determined by the abortion doctor.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] After viability a woman can obtain an abortion for health reasons, which the Court defined broadly to include psychological well-being in the decision *Doe v.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] From the 1970s, and the spread of second-wave feminism, abortion and reproductive rights became unifying issues among various women's rights groups in Canada, the United States, the Netherlands, Britain, Norway, France, Germany, and Italy.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In 2015, in the wake of the House of Representatives' vote to defund Planned Parenthood, Lindy West, Amelia Bonow and Kimberly Morrison launched ShoutYourAbortion to "remind supporters and critics alike abortion is a legal right to anyone who wants or needs it".
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In 2019, the You Know Me movement started as a response to the successful 2019 passage of fetal heartbeat bills in five states in the United States, most notably the passing of anti-abortion laws in Georgia (House Bill 381), Ohio (House Bill 68) and Alabama (House Bill 314).
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] This movement was started off by actress Busy Philipps because she had previously had an abortion when she was a teen.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The actress and many others believe that it is important for women to speak up and shift the narrative, especially because abortion is such a taboo subject.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In the mid-19th century, concerns around abortion only consisted of the danger of a woman being poisoned and risking her health, not because of religion, ethics, or diplomacy.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Ending a pregnancy before the fetus began movement, or "post-quickening" was only a wrongdoing, not a crime.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The laws that were against abortions post-quickening removals were put in place to protect the well-being of the women that were pregnant, not the fetal life.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] It was more common for women to die during early terminations due to the usage of pre-owned instruments as opposed to natural abortifacients.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Some women who engaged in quickening abortions were not prosecuted because there was no evidence and quickening was hard to prove.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Between 1900 and 1965, there were not any anti-abortion movements or rallies because states had already passed a law banning abortions at all levels included the prescription of drugs or undergoing procedures.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The only exception for a woman to proceed with an abortion without worrying about breaking any anti-abortion laws is if a licensed physician were to prove that the abortion was for the protection of the mother's life.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion care providers and women who had obtained an abortion were pestered by courts and prosecutors.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In the 1960s, some states began to request changes, around the abortion law, from their states.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In 1959, a group of experts set up a model enactment that supported the advancement of the fetus removal laws that were put in place.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] These experts suggested that the abortion laws should exempt women that were sexually assaulted, whose babies well-being were to be questioned and whose babies that were to be born out of its true, natural or original state.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The Abortion Rights Movement became a cultural shift in The United States about the intentions of reproduction and abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Wade* verdict changed the abortion laws altogether, making abortion legal.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Many physicians and healthcare professionals jeopardized their medical licenses, risked being put in prison and fined by the state because they wanted to continue to provide abortions.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] There were more than 1,000 abortion laws passed and enacted between 2011 and 2019 that limited access to abortion procedures.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Some of these laws forbid a woman getting an abortion past a certain gestational age and was also based on race and specific pregnancy conditions.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Other laws were established that ban particular abortion methods.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Targeted regulation of abortion providers (TRAP) was put in place to target abortion clinics by demanding unnecessary requirements that made it hard for women to get an abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Opponents of abortion rights claim that these requirements are for the safety of the mother and child, but that has not been scientifically proven.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] TRAP has placed limitations on abortion facilities to make it more difficult for them to provide abortion services that will essentially force them to not provide abortion services at all.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] TRAP policies have been put in place by 26 states as of 2020.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] During the pandemic, numerous states prohibited non-essential medical procedures, including abortion services.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Policymakers in twelve states saw this as a chance to certify abortion as non-essential, therefore ending services.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Jackson Women's Health Organization overturned Roe v.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Wade, removing the federal constitutional right to abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] This left abortion laws and restrictions up to each individual state.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] South Africa allows abortion on demand under its Choice on Termination of Pregnancy Act.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Most African nations, however, have abortion bans except in cases where the woman's life or health is at risk.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] A number of abortion-rights international organizations have made altering abortion laws and expanding family planning services in sub-Saharan Africa and the developing world a top priority.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] But there are only five countries in Africa where abortion is legal and those countries are Cape Verde, South Africa, Tunisia, Mozambique and Saõ Tome & Principe.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] 8.2 million abortions were performed each year in Africa.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] This number increased drastically compared to the 4.6 million abortions that were performed during 1990–1994.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] But this increased number of abortions is due to the increase of women that are reproducing at a young age.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Approximately 93% of women within their reproductive age live in countries that have very restrictive abortion laws and abortion is only legal in 10 out of 54 African countries, leading to fewer women not being able to obtain a safe procedure.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The World Health Organization only recommends trained personnel when performing induced abortions but not many women in Africa have access to trained professionals who are able to provide them with the best service to decrease the number of complications due to abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Approximately 1.6 million women are treated for abortion-related complications and only one in four abortions in Africa are safe.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Africa has the highest number of deaths that are related to abortion and this is due to the most common complication of abortion that consist of excessive blood loss and an incomplete abortion that can lead to an infection.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] During 2010–2014, 36 million abortions were performed in Asia.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Majority of abortions occurred in Central and South Asia at a rate of 16 million in India and Asia and 13 million in China alone.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Although the abortions performed in Asia are not known, there is an estimated 4.6 million women who are treated because they have complications due to the performance of an unsafe abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The major complication of abortion is an incomplete abortion where a woman can experience an immoderate amount of blood loss and can develop an infection.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Less common complications of abortion include a woman going into septic shock, damaging the internal organs and causing the peritoneum to be inflamed, all due to the unclean and unsterilized instruments that are being used doing the procedure.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Untreated complications from abortions can leave women to experience negative health consequences for life that include infertility, chronic pain, inflammation of the reproductive organs and pelvic inflammatory disease.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Unsafe abortions go deeper than just a woman's health but they lead to reduced productivity for women increased costs to an already struggling family.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Although it is not completely known, a drug known as misoprostol is used to perform abortions in Asian countries and evidence shows that the sales of this drug has increased in Asia over the course of years.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] On record, out of all the pregnancies in Asia, 27 percent of them end in abortions.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] This is the reason for the Asia Safe Abortion Partnership (ASAP).
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] This program was formed to increase the accessibility to safe and legal abortions and health care that is needed after any abortion service.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] 50 countries occupy Asia and out of those 50, 17 countries do not have a restriction on abortions excluding, gestational limits and permission from a spouse or parent.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] ASAP satisfies the demand for safe and accessible abortions through educational and advocacy.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] By grouping with other countries to promote advocacy networks, ASAP has created a worldwide and generational feminist power that advocates for women's abortion rights, autonomy and dignity.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Anti-abortion groups have tried their best to discriminate the reproductive autonomy of women but ASAP has members spread across 20 countries that promote the women's movement for abortion rights, laws, and access.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Even though abortion is legal in Asia, that does not mean that women always have access or adequate health care during these times.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] For example, abortions in India have been legal since 1951 but women who are particularly poor or marginalized make up 50% of unsafe abortions.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Women in the Philippines are more than likely to undergo an unsafe and unsanitary abortion causing around 1,000 death annually due to abortion complications.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The Philippines along with Iraq and Laos are the countries that has not made abortion legal, excluding legal exceptions, therefore they have not made it available to where women can have admissions to legal abortions that are safe for them and their bodies.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Countries such as Afghanistan, Thailand, China and Lebanon, have all been impacted by the determined long-term feminist motion by ASAP for women's abortion rights.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] This work ranges from workshops, journalists, advocates to menstrual management, violence against women, and issues surrounded unplanned pregnancies.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] "Youth champions" were created by ASAP to share the knowledge that they have learned to their peers about sexual activity, abortions, women's rights and reproductions, reproductive health, and the abortion rights movement in general.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Chapter XXIX of the Penal Code of Japan makes abortion illegal in Japan.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Other people, including the mother herself, trying to abort the fetus can be punished by the law.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] People trying to practice abortion without the consent of the woman can also be punished, including the doctors.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion has been illegal in South Korea since 1953 but on April 11, 2019, South Korea's Constitutional Court ruled the abortion ban unconstitutional and called for the law to be amended.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The Constitutional Court has taken into consideration abortion-rights cases by women because they find the abortion ban as unconstitutional.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] To help support the legalization of abortion in South Korea, thousands of advocates compiled a petition for the Blue House to consider lifting the ban.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Due to the abortion ban, this has led to many dangerous self-induced abortions and other illegal practices of abortion that needs more attention.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] This is why there are advocates challenging the law to put into perspective the negative factors this abortion ban brings.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] By making abortion illegal in South Korea, this also creates an issue when it comes to women's rights and their own rights to their bodies.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] As a result, many women's advocate groups were created and acted together to protest against the abortion ban law.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Global Day of Action is a form of protest that advocates to make a change and bring more awareness to global warming.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] During this protest, a group of feminist Korean advocates called, "The Joint Action for Reproductive Justice" connected with one another to promote concerns that requires more attention and needs a quick change such as making abortion legal.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] By combining different advocate groups that serves different purposes and their own goals they want to achieve into one event, it helps promote all the different aspects of reality that needs to change.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In 1920, under the leadership of Vladimir Lenin, Russia became the first country in the world to legally permit abortion, no matter the circumstances.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] But in the 20th century, the laws surrounding abortion were repeatedly modified between the years of 1936 and 1955.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] According to data from the United Nations in 2010, Russia had the highest rates of abortion per woman of reproduction.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Results from the abortion rates of China and Russia were compared and out of a population of 1.3 billion people, China only reported 13 million abortions, a huge difference when contrasted to the population in Russia of 143 million people with 1.2 million abortions.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Since abortion was illegal in the Russian Empire, it was not recognized in the Domostroi.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The Domostroi was a set of tasks that were to be followed that were structured around rules, instructions surrounded by religious, social and domestic issues that were centered within the Russian Society.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] These rules enforced respect and compliance to God and the church.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Different rulers had different views about abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] During Romanov's reign, abortion was illegal, frowned up, and if a woman were to go through with an abortion, her punishment was death.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] But after Romanov's reign ended, Peter the Great lifted the punishment of death for abortions but it was still considered a serious issue in 1917.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Before the punishment for abortions was death, according to the Russian Penal Code that dates back to 1462–1463, women were dispossessed of their basic human and civil rights and banned from the city or they were forced into hard labor.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] These harsh treatments and illegality surrounded around abortion still did not stop women from pursuing abortions.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] "Black Market" abortions were known as unauthorized and discreet procedures done by women who have experience in childbirth.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] These women were known as older women that were midwives and rural midwives, respectfully.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Although these women were not abortion care providers, they were the only accessible obstetric personnel that women could go to without facing the harsh punishment and consequences forced upon by the Russian Society.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Since adequate medical care was not provided for women looking to terminate their pregnancy, midwives and nurses from villages were trained to care for these women the best to their ability, but of course with illegal abortions there are always repercussions.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] During the Soviet period in Russia, abortions ranked as the highest rates world-wide.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] After the Soviet period ended inn the Russian union, abortion numbers decreased with further enforced sex education courses and use of contraceptive birth control.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion was illegal in the Republic of Ireland except when the woman's life was threatened by a medical condition (including risk of suicide), since a 1983 referendum (aka 8th Amendment) amended the constitution.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Subsequent amendments in 1992 (after the X Case) – the thirteenth and fourteenth – guaranteed the right to travel abroad (for abortions) and to distribute and obtain information of "lawful services" available in other countries.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Two proposals to remove suicide risk as a ground for abortion were rejected by the people, in a referendum in 1992 and in 2002.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Thousands of women get around the ban by privately traveling to the other European countries (typically Britain and the Netherlands) to undergo termination, or by ordering abortion pills from Women on Web online and taking them in Ireland.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Sinn Féin, the Labour Party, Social Democrats, Green Party, Communist Party, Socialist Party and Irish Republican Socialist Party have made their official policies to support abortion rights.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Mainstream center-right parties such as Fianna Fáil and Fine Gael do not have official policies on abortion rights but allow their members to take a conscience vote in support of abortion in limited circumstances.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Aontú, founded in January 2019, is firmly anti-abortionist and seeks to "protect the right to life".
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] After the death of Savita Halappanavar in 2012, there has been a renewed campaign to repeal the eighth amendment and legalize abortion.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] As of January 2017, the Irish government has set up a citizens assembly to look at the issue.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Their proposals, broadly supported by a cross-party Oireachtas committee, include repeal of the 8th Amendment, unrestricted access to abortion for the first 12 weeks of pregnancy and no-term limits for special cases of fatal foetal abnormalities, rape and incest.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] A referendum on the repealing of the 8th Amendment was held on May 25, 2018.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Together for Yes, a cross-society group formed from the Coalition to Repeal the 8th Amendment, the National Women's Council of Ireland and the Abortion Rights Campaign, were the official campaign group for repeal in the referendum.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Activists utilized social media to bring the narrative of women's voices to the forefront of the campaign, making clear that the Eighth Amendment was dangerous for pregnant women to try and encourage voters to vote in favor of repeal.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The 67% majority in favor of repeal is a testament to these stories and the women who braved the public Twitter sphere to change the law around women's reproductive lives.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Despite being part of the United Kingdom, abortion remained illegal in Northern Ireland, except in cases when the woman is threatened by a medical condition, physical or mental, until 2019.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Women seeking abortions had to travel to England.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In October 2019, abortion up to 12 weeks was legalized, to begin in April 2020, but remains near-unobtainable.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Poland initially held abortion to be legal in 1958 by the communist government, but was later banned after restoration of democracy in 1989.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Currently, abortion is illegal in all cases except for rape or when the fetus or mother is in fatal conditions.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The wide spread of Catholic Church in Poland within the country has made abortion socially 'unacceptable'.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The Pope has had major influence on the acceptance of abortion within Poland.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Several landmark court cases have had substantial influence on the current status of abortion, including *Tysiac v Poland*.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In the United Kingdom, the Abortion Act 1967 legalized abortion on a wide number of grounds, except in Northern Ireland.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] 4. shows there is evidence of extreme fetal abnormality i.e. the child would be seriously physically or mentally handicapped after birth and during life.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] However, the criterion of risk to mental and physical health is applied broadly, and *de facto* makes abortion available on demand, though this still requires the consent of two National Health Service doctors.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Abortions in Great Britain are provided at no out-of-pocket cost to the patient by the NHS.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The Labour Party and the Liberal Democrats are predominantly pro-abortion-rights parties, though with significant minorities in each either holding more restrictive definitions of the right to choose, or subscribing to an anti-abortion analysis.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The Conservative Party is more evenly split between both camps and its former leader, David Cameron, supports abortion on demand in the early stages of pregnancy.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion laws in the Middle East reflect variation of opinions.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Some countries permit abortion in cases involving a pregnant woman's well-being, fetal impairment, and rape.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion was widely practiced during the colonial period, and allowed a longer term termination.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] By the 19th century, progressive interpretations cut the abortion time limit down to the first trimester.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] However, a 2008 World Health Organization report estimated 900,000 unsafe abortion occurred each year in the Middle Eastern and Northern Africa regions.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] While many countries have decriminalized abortions and made it more accessible, there are still a few remaining countries yet to do so.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] In April 2005, the Iranian Parliament approved a new bill easing the conditions by also allowing abortion in certain cases when the fetus shows signs of handicap.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Legal abortion is now allowed if the mother's life is in danger, and also in cases of fetal abnormalities that makes it not viable after birth (such as anencephaly) or produce difficulties for mother to take care of it after birth, such as major thalassemia or bilateral polycystic kidney disease.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion-rights advocacy in the United States is centered in the United States abortion-rights movement.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Across the world, there are only four countries in which abortion is completely banned.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Honduras, Dominican Republic, Nicaragua, and El Salvador have yet to legalize abortions, even if it is for the woman's health and safety.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Since 2018, there have been no changes in the laws regarding abortion in these Latin-America countries.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The Ministry of Public Health collected data that showed nearly half the pregnancies in the Dominican Republic alone are unwanted or unplanned; often stemming from incest or rape.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Women in South America continue fighting for their rights and protection, but there has been no recent call of action.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Because Argentina has been very restrictive against abortion, reliable reporting on abortion rates is unavailable.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Argentina has long been a strongly Catholic country, and protesters seeking legalized abortion in 2013 directed anger toward the Catholic Church.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] On December 11, 2020, after a 20-hour debate, the Chamber of Deputies voted 131 to 117 (6 abstentions) to approve a bill legalizing abortion up to 14 weeks after conception.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The bill's passing resulted in large-scale celebrations by abortion rights activists who had long campaigned for it.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] The Argentine Senate approved the bill 38–29 on December 29, and it is expected to be signed by President Alberto Fernandez.
[src:infertility/abortion-rights-movements] Argentina will become the fourth Latin American country to legalize abortion.
[src:infertility/abraham] The story of the life of Abraham, as told in the narrative of the Book of Genesis in the Hebrew Bible, revolves around the themes of blessing and promise, especially the promise of progeny and land.
[src:infertility/abraham] He is said to have been called by God to leave the house of his father Terah and settle in the land of Canaan, which God now promises to Abraham and his progeny.
[src:infertility/abraham] This promise is subsequently inherited by Isaac, Abraham's son by his wife Sarah, while Isaac's half-brother Ishmael is also promised that he will be the founder of a great nation.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham purchases a tomb (the Cave of the Patriarchs) at Hebron to be Sarah's grave, thus establishing his right to the land; and, in the second generation, his heir Isaac is married to a woman from his own kin to earn his parents' approval.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham later marries Keturah and has six more sons; but, on his death, when he is buried beside Sarah, it is Isaac who receives "all Abraham's goods" while the other sons receive only "gifts".
[src:infertility/abraham] Most scholars view the patriarchal age, along with the Exodus, as a late literary construct that does not relate to any particular historical era.
[src:infertility/abraham] Many scholars believe the Abraham traditions developed orally over centuries, before being incorporated into the Book of Genesis during the Persian period of Yehud, where they helped shape post-exilic Jewish identity and support competing claims to the land.
[src:infertility/abraham] The storytelling method used here is the “obstacle story,” a literary device renowned for its enduring and universal popularity across cultures and eras.
[src:infertility/abraham] The Abraham cycle is not structured by a unified plot centered on a conflict and its resolution or a problem and its solution.
[src:infertility/abraham] The episodes are often only loosely linked, and the sequence is not always logical.
[src:infertility/abraham] The story portrays Abraham gradually assuming the role of the ideal religious person amid themes of blessing and promise, especially the promise of progeny and land.
[src:infertility/abraham] These themes form "narrative programs" set out in Genesis 11:27–31 concerning the sterility of Sarah and Genesis 12:1–3 in which Abraham is ordered to leave the land of his birth for the land God will show him.
[src:infertility/abraham] Terah, the ninth in descent from Noah, was the father of Abram, Nahor and Haran (Hebrew: הָרָן *Hārān*).
[src:infertility/abraham] Haran was the father of Lot, who was Abram's nephew; the family lived in Ur of the Chaldees.
[src:infertility/abraham] Haran died there while Terah was still alive.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abram married Sarah (Sarai) but, unlike Nahor and his wife Milcah, they were childless.
[src:infertility/abraham] Genesis 11 records that Terah, Abram, Sarai, and Lot departed for Canaan, but settled in a place named Haran (Hebrew: חָרָן *Ḥārān*), where Terah died at the age of 205.
[src:infertility/abraham] Then the narrative in Genesis 12 shows that God told Abram to leave his country and his kindred, and go to a land that God would show him, and promised to make of him a great nation, bless him, make his name great, bless them that bless him, and curse them who may curse him.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abram was 75 years old when he and Sarai left Haran with his nephew Lot, and their possessions and people that they had acquired, and they traveled to Shechem in Canaan.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abram built an altar to God in Shechem, and later he built another altar between Bethel and Ai.
[src:infertility/abraham] From there the party travelled to the Negev, or to the south.
[src:infertility/abraham] According to some exegetes, like Nahmanides, Abram was actually born in Haran and he later relocated to Ur, while some of his family remained in Haran.
[src:infertility/abraham] There was a severe famine in the land of Canaan, so that Abram, Lot, and their households traveled to Egypt.
[src:infertility/abraham] On the way Abram told Sarai to tell the Egyptians she was his sister, so that the Egyptians would not kill him.
[src:infertility/abraham] When they entered Egypt, the Pharaoh's officials praised Sarai's beauty to Pharaoh, and they took her into the palace and gave Abram goods in exchange.
[src:infertility/abraham] God afflicted Pharaoh and his household with plagues, which led Pharaoh to try to find out what was wrong.
[src:infertility/abraham] Upon discovering that Sarai was a married woman, Pharaoh demanded that Abram and Sarai leave, escorting them to the frontier.
[src:infertility/abraham] When they lived for a while in the Negev after being banished from Egypt and came back to the Bethel and Ai area, Abram's and Lot's sizable herds occupied the same pastures.
[src:infertility/abraham] This became a problem for the herdsmen, who were assigned to each family's cattle.
[src:infertility/abraham] The conflicts between herdsmen had become so troublesome that Abram suggested that Lot choose a separate area, either on the left hand or on the right hand, that there be no conflict between them.
[src:infertility/abraham] Lot decided to go eastward to the plain of Jordan, where the land was well watered everywhere as far as Zoara, and he dwelled in the cities of the plain toward Sodom.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abram went south to Hebron and settled in the plain of Mamre, where he built another altar to worship God.
[src:infertility/abraham] During the rebellion of the Jordan River cities, Sodom and Gomorrah, against Elam, Abram's nephew, Lot, was taken prisoner along with his entire household by the invading Elamite forces.
[src:infertility/abraham] The Elamite army came to collect the spoils of war, after having just defeated the king of Sodom's armies.
[src:infertility/abraham] Lot and his family, at the time, were settled on the outskirts of the Kingdom of Sodom which made them a visible target.
[src:infertility/abraham] One person who escaped capture came and told Abram what happened.
[src:infertility/abraham] Once Abram received this news, he immediately assembled 318 trained servants.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abram's force headed north in pursuit of the Elamite army, who were already worn down from the Battle of Siddim.
[src:infertility/abraham] When they caught up with them at Dan, Abram devised a battle plan by splitting his group into more than one unit, and launched a night raid.
[src:infertility/abraham] Not only were they able to free the captives, Abram's unit chased and slaughtered the Elamite King Chedorlaomer at Hobah, just north of Damascus.
[src:infertility/abraham] They freed Lot, as well as his household and possessions, and recovered all of the goods from Sodom that had been taken.
[src:infertility/abraham] Upon Abram's return, Sodom's king came out to meet with him in the Valley of Shaveh, the "king's dale".
[src:infertility/abraham] Also, Melchizedek king of Salem (Jerusalem), a priest of El Elyon, brought out bread and wine and blessed Abram and God.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abram then gave Melchizedek a tenth of everything.
[src:infertility/abraham] The king of Sodom then offered to let Abram keep all the possessions if he would merely return his people.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abram declined to accept anything other than the share to which his allies were entitled.
[src:infertility/abraham] Some time after these events, the voice of the LORD came to Abram in a vision, promising him a "reward", namely a son, and repeating the promise of the land and descendants as numerous as the stars.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abram was childless until then, and had anticipated that Eliezer of Damascus, head of his household, would inherit his estate on his death.
[src:infertility/abraham] He was to be rewarded in virtue of his trust in God.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abram and God then made a covenant ceremony, and God told Abram of the future bondage of his people "in a land that is not theirs", referring to Egypt.
[src:infertility/abraham] God then described to Abram the land that his offspring would claim: the land of the Kenites, Kenizzites, Kadmonites, Hittites, Perizzites, the Rephaim, Amorites, Canaanites, Girgashites, and Jebusites.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abram and Sarai tried to make sense of how he would become a progenitor of nations, because after 10 years of living in Canaan, no child had been born.
[src:infertility/abraham] Sarai then offered her Egyptian slave, Hagar, to Abram with the intention that she would bear him a son.
[src:infertility/abraham] After Hagar found she was pregnant, she began to despise her mistress, Sarai.
[src:infertility/abraham] Sarai responded by mistreating Hagar, and Hagar fled into the wilderness.
[src:infertility/abraham] An angel spoke with Hagar at the fountain on the way to Shur.
[src:infertility/abraham] He instructed her to return to Abram's camp and that her son would be "a wild ass of a man; his hand shall be against every man, and every man's hand against him; and he shall dwell in the face of all his brethren." She was told to call her son Ishmael.
[src:infertility/abraham] Hagar then called God who spoke to her "El-roi", ("Thou God seest me": KJV).
[src:infertility/abraham] From that day onward, the well was called Beer-lahai-roi, ("The well of him that liveth and seeth me": KJV margin), located between Kadesh and Bered.
[src:infertility/abraham] She then did as she was instructed by returning to her mistress in order to have her child.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abram was 86 years of age when Ishmael was born.
[src:infertility/abraham] Thirteen years later, when Abram was 99 years of age, God appeared to Abram again and called upon him to be "perfect" or "blameless", so that God could make a covenant with him.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abram fell or bowed to the ground in a gesture of reverence, and God gave Abram a new name: he was now to be called "Abraham".
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham means "father of a multitude": he would be "a father of many nations".
[src:infertility/abraham] The new name denotes a new stage in Abraham's life.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham then received God's instructions concerning circumcision.
[src:infertility/abraham] God also declared Sarai's new name to be "Sarah", blessed her, and told Abraham, "I will give thee a son also of her".
[src:infertility/abraham] Immediately after Abraham's encounter with God, he had his entire household of men, including himself (age 99) and Ishmael (age 13), circumcised.
[src:infertility/abraham] Not long afterward, during the heat of the day, Abraham had been sitting at the entrance of his tent by the terebinths of Mamre.
[src:infertility/abraham] He looked up and saw three men in the presence of God.
[src:infertility/abraham] Then he ran and bowed to the ground to welcome them.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham then offered to wash their feet and fetch them a morsel of bread, to which they assented.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham rushed to Sarah's tent to order ash cakes made from choice flour, then he ordered a servant-boy to prepare a choice calf.
[src:infertility/abraham] When all was prepared, he set curds, milk and the calf before them, waiting on them, under a tree, as they ate.
[src:infertility/abraham] One of the visitors told Abraham that upon his return next year, Sarah would have a son.
[src:infertility/abraham] While at the tent entrance, Sarah overheard what was said and she laughed to herself about the prospect of having a child at their ages.
[src:infertility/abraham] The visitor inquired of Abraham why Sarah laughed at bearing a child at her age, as nothing is too hard for God.
[src:infertility/abraham] After eating, Abraham and the three visitors got up.
[src:infertility/abraham] Accompanied by Abraham, the visitors walked over to the peak that overlooked the "cities of the plain" to discuss the fate of Sodom and Gomorrah for their detestable sins that were so great, they moved God to action.
[src:infertility/abraham] Because of God's promise to Abraham regarding his destiny, God revealed plans to assess what these cities have done and confer judgment on them.
[src:infertility/abraham] At this point, the two other visitors left for Sodom.
[src:infertility/abraham] Then Abraham turned to God and pleaded decrementally with Him (from fifty persons to less) that "if there were at least ten righteous men found in the city, would not God spare the city?" For the sake of ten righteous people, God declared that he would not destroy the city.
[src:infertility/abraham] When the two visitors arrived in Sodom to conduct their report, they planned on staying in the city square.
[src:infertility/abraham] However, Abraham's nephew, Lot, met with them and strongly insisted that these two "men" stay at his house for the night.
[src:infertility/abraham] A rally of men stood outside of Lot's home and demanded that Lot bring out his guests so that they may "know" (v.
[src:infertility/abraham] However, Lot objected and offered his virgin daughters who had not "known" (v.
[src:infertility/abraham] They rejected that notion and sought to break down Lot's door to get to his male guests, thus confirming the wickedness of the city and portending their imminent destruction.
[src:infertility/abraham] Early the next morning, Abraham went to the place where he stood before God.
[src:infertility/abraham] He "looked out toward Sodom and Gomorrah" and saw what became of the cities of the plain, where not even "ten righteous" (v.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham moved to live between Kadesh and Shur, settling in Gerar, later associated with the Philistines".
[src:infertility/abraham] While he was living in there, Abraham openly claimed that Sarah was his sister, and she confirmed this assertion, leading King Abimelech to call for Sarah to be brought to him.
[src:infertility/abraham] God then came to Abimelech in a dream and declared that taking her would result in his death, because she was a man's wife.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abimelech had not laid hands on her, so he inquired if he would also slay a righteous nation, especially since Abraham and Sarah had claimed that they were siblings.
[src:infertility/abraham] In response, God told Abimelech that he did indeed have a blameless heart and that is why he continued to exist.
[src:infertility/abraham] However, should he not return the wife of Abraham back to him, God would surely destroy Abimelech and his entire household.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abimelech was informed that Abraham was a prophet who would pray for him.
[src:infertility/abraham] Early next morning, Abimelech informed his servants of his dream and approached Abraham inquiring as to why he had brought such great guilt upon his kingdom.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham stated that he thought there was no fear of God in that place, and that they might kill him for his wife.
[src:infertility/abraham] Further, Abimelech gave Abraham a thousand pieces of silver to serve as Sarah's vindication before all.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham then prayed for Abimelech and his household, since God had stricken the women with infertility because of the taking of Sarah.
[src:infertility/abraham] Two incidents follow in which Abraham and Abimelech resolve issues by agreement.
[src:infertility/abraham] Firstly, Abimelech, supported by Phicol, the chief of his troops, secures from the patriarch an agreement that he will act honestly in his dealings with Abimelech and his descendants, reciprocating the manner in which Abimelech says he has treated Abraham.
[src:infertility/abraham] Subsequently, a specific issue arises in relation to a well which Abraham has dug but which Abimelech's servants have taken over.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abimelech and Phicol approached Abraham because of a dispute over the well.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham reproached Abimelech due to his servants' aggressive attacks and the seizing of the well.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abimelech claimed ignorance of the incident.
[src:infertility/abraham] Then Abraham offered a pact by providing sheep and oxen to Abimelech.
[src:infertility/abraham] Further, to attest that Abraham was the one who had dug the well, he also gave Abimelech seven ewes for proof.
[src:infertility/abraham] Because of this sworn oath, they called the place of this well Beersheba.
[src:infertility/abraham] After Abimelech and Phicol headed back to Philistia, Abraham planted a tamarisk grove in Beersheba and called upon "the name of the LORD, the everlasting God".
[src:infertility/abraham] As had been prophesied at Mamre the previous year, Sarah became pregnant and bore a son to Abraham, on the first anniversary of the covenant of circumcision.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham was "an hundred years old" when his son, whom he named Isaac, was born, and he circumcised him when he was eight days old.
[src:infertility/abraham] During the celebration, however, Sarah found Ishmael mocking; an observation that would begin to clarify the birthright of Isaac.
[src:infertility/abraham] Ishmael was fourteen years old when Abraham's son Isaac was born to Sarah.
[src:infertility/abraham] When she found Ishmael teasing Isaac, Sarah told Abraham to send both Ishmael and Hagar away.
[src:infertility/abraham] She declared that Ishmael would not share in Isaac's inheritance.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham was greatly distressed by his wife's words and sought the advice of his God.
[src:infertility/abraham] God told Abraham not to be distressed but to do as his wife commanded.
[src:infertility/abraham] God reassured Abraham that "in Isaac shall seed be called to thee." He also said Ishmael would make a nation, "because he is thy seed".
[src:infertility/abraham] Early the next morning, Abraham brought Hagar and Ishmael out together.
[src:infertility/abraham] He gave her bread and water and sent them away.
[src:infertility/abraham] The two wandered in the wilderness of Beersheba until her bottle of water was completely consumed.
[src:infertility/abraham] In a moment of despair, she burst into tears.
[src:infertility/abraham] After God heard the boy's voice, an angel of the Lord confirmed to Hagar that he would become a great nation, and will be "living on his sword".
[src:infertility/abraham] A well of water then appeared so that it saved their lives.
[src:infertility/abraham] As the boy grew, he became a skilled archer living in the wilderness of Paran.
[src:infertility/abraham] Eventually his mother found a wife for Ishmael from her home country, the land of Egypt.
[src:infertility/abraham] At some point in Isaac's youth, Abraham was commanded by God to offer his son up as a sacrifice in the land of Moriah.
[src:infertility/abraham] The patriarch traveled three days until he came to the mount that God told him of.
[src:infertility/abraham] He then commanded the servants to remain while he and Isaac proceeded alone into the mount.
[src:infertility/abraham] Isaac carried the wood upon which he would be sacrificed.
[src:infertility/abraham] Along the way, Isaac asked his father where the animal for the burnt offering was, to which Abraham replied "God will provide himself a lamb for a burnt offering".
[src:infertility/abraham] Just as Abraham was about to sacrifice his son, he was interrupted by the angel of the Lord, and he saw behind him a "ram caught in a thicket by his horns", which he sacrificed instead of his son.
[src:infertility/abraham] The place was later named as Jehovah-jireh.
[src:infertility/abraham] For his obedience he received another promise of numerous descendants and abundant prosperity.
[src:infertility/abraham] After this event, Abraham went to Beersheba.
[src:infertility/abraham] Sarah died, and Abraham buried her in the Cave of the Patriarchs (the "cave of Machpelah"), near Hebron which he had purchased along with the adjoining field from Ephron the Hittite.
[src:infertility/abraham] After the death of Sarah, Abraham took another wife, a concubine named Keturah, and together they had six sons: Zimran, Jokshan, Medan, Midian, Ishbak, and Shuah.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham lived to see Isaac marry Rebekah, and to see the birth of his twin grandsons Jacob and Esau.
[src:infertility/abraham] He died at age 175, and was buried in the cave of Machpelah by his sons Isaac and Ishmael.
[src:infertility/abraham] In the early and middle 20th century, leading archaeologists such as William F.
[src:infertility/abraham] Ernest Wright and biblical scholars such as Albrecht Alt and John Bright believed that the patriarchs and matriarchs were either real individuals or believable composites of people who lived in the "patriarchal age", the 2nd millennium BCE.
[src:infertility/abraham] However, in the 1970s, new arguments concerning Israel's past and the biblical texts challenged these views; these arguments can be found in Thomas L.
[src:infertility/abraham] Thompson's *The Historicity of the Patriarchal Narratives* (1974), and John Van Seters' *Abraham in History and Tradition* (1975).
[src:infertility/abraham] Thompson, a literary scholar, based his argument on archaeology and ancient texts.
[src:infertility/abraham] His thesis centered on the lack of compelling evidence that the patriarchs lived in the 2nd millennium BCE, and noted how certain biblical texts reflected first millennium conditions and concerns.
[src:infertility/abraham] Van Seters examined the patriarchal stories and argued that their names, social milieu, and messages strongly suggested that they were Iron Age creations.
[src:infertility/abraham] Van Seters' and Thompson's works were a paradigm shift in biblical scholarship and archaeology, which gradually led scholars to no longer consider the patriarchal narratives as historical.
[src:infertility/abraham] Some conservative scholars attempted to defend the Patriarchal narratives in the following years, but this has not found acceptance among scholars.
[src:infertility/abraham] By the beginning of the 21st century, archaeologists had stopped trying to recover any context that would make Abraham, Isaac or Jacob credible historical figures.
[src:infertility/abraham] At some stage the oral traditions became part of the written tradition of the Pentateuch; a majority of scholars believe this stage belongs to the Persian period, roughly 520–320 BCE.
[src:infertility/abraham] The mechanisms by which this came about remain unknown, but there are currently at least two hypotheses.
[src:infertility/abraham] The completion of the Torah and its elevation to the centre of post-Exilic Judaism was as much or more about combining older texts as writing new ones – the final Pentateuch was based on existing traditions.
[src:infertility/abraham] The Book of Isaiah similarly testifies to tension between the people of Judah and the returning post-Exilic Jews (the "gôlâ"), stating that God is the father of Israel and that Israel's history begins with the Exodus and not with Abraham.
[src:infertility/abraham] According to Nissim Amzallag, the Book of Genesis portrays Abraham as having an Amorite origin, arguing that the patriarch's provenance from the region of Harran as described in Genesis 11:31 associates him with the territory of the Amorite homeland.
[src:infertility/abraham] He also notes parallels between the biblical narrative and the Amorite migration into the Southern Levant in the 2nd millennium BCE.
[src:infertility/abraham] Alan Millard argues that the name Abram is of Amorite origin and that it is attested in Mari as *ʾabī-rām*.
[src:infertility/abraham] He also suggests that the Patriarch's name corresponds to a form typical of the Middle Bronze Age and not of later periods.
[src:infertility/abraham] Some papers identify Abraham with the Amorite chieftain Abum, and his son Ishmael with Sumulael.
[src:infertility/abraham] The orientalist Mario Liverani has proposed to see in the name Abraham the eponymous ancestor of a 13th-century BCE tribe, the Raham, mentioned in a stele of Seti I found at Beth-Shean and dating back to around 1289 BCE.
[src:infertility/abraham] The tribe probably lived in the area surrounding or close to Beth-Shean, in Galilee (the stele in fact refers to battles that took place in the area).
[src:infertility/abraham] Liverani hypothesized that the members of the tribe of Raham called themselves "sons of Raham" (**Banu-Raham*), so that the name of their eponymous ancestor would have been "father of Raham" (**Abu-Raham*), that being the name of the patriarch Abraham.
[src:infertility/abraham] Finkelstein and Römer considered Abraham as ancestor who was worshiped in Hebron, with the oldest tradition of him possibly being about the altar he built in Hebron.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham is given a high position of respect in three major world faiths, Judaism, Christianity, and Islam.
[src:infertility/abraham] In Judaism, he is the founding father of the covenant, the special relationship between the Jewish people and God—leading to the belief that the Jews are the chosen people of God.
[src:infertility/abraham] In Christianity, Paul the Apostle taught that Abraham's faith in God, preceding receipt of the Mosaic law, made him the prototype of all believers, Jewish or gentile; and in Islam, he is seen as a link in the chain of prophets that begins with Adam and culminates in Muhammad.
[src:infertility/abraham] Specifically through Jacob, renamed "Israel" in Genesis 35:10, both "a nation and a company of nations" would arise, and the promise that his descendants would become a multitude of nations is maintained through Jacob's blessing of his grandson, Ephraim, in Genesis 48:19.
[src:infertility/abraham] In Jewish tradition, Abraham is called *Avraham Avinu* (אברהם אבינו), "our father Abraham", signifying that he is both the biological progenitor of the Jews and the father of Judaism, the first Jew.
[src:infertility/abraham] His story is read in the weekly Torah reading portions, predominantly in the parashot: Lech-Lecha (לֶךְ-לְךָ), Vayeira (וַיֵּרָא), Chayei Sarah (חַיֵּי שָׂרָה), and Toledot (תּוֹלְדֹת).
[src:infertility/abraham] Hanan bar Rava taught in Abba Arikha's name that Abraham's mother was named ʾĂmatlaʾy bat Karnebo.
[src:infertility/abraham] Hiyya bar Abba taught that Abraham worked in Teraḥ's idol shop in his youth.
[src:infertility/abraham] According to the *Legends of the Jews*, God created heaven and earth for the sake of the merits of Abraham.
[src:infertility/abraham] After the biblical flood, Abraham was the only one among the pious who solemnly swore never to forsake God, studied in the house of Noah and Shem to learn about the "Ways of God", and continued the line of High Priest from Noah and Shem, assigning the office to Levi and his seed forever.
[src:infertility/abraham] Before leaving his father's land, Abraham was miraculously saved from the fiery furnace of Nimrod following his brave action of breaking the idols of the Chaldeans into pieces.
[src:infertility/abraham] During his sojourning in Canaan, Abraham was accustomed to extend hospitality to travelers and strangers and taught how to praise God also knowledge of God to those who had received his kindness.
[src:infertility/abraham] Along with Isaac and Jacob, he is the one whose name would appear united with God, as God in Judaism is called *Elohei Avraham, Elohei Yitzchak, vEilohei Ya'akov* ("God of Abraham, God of Isaac, and God of Jacob").
[src:infertility/abraham] He was also mentioned as the father of thirty nations.
[src:infertility/abraham] In Mandaeism, Abraham (Classical Mandaic: ࡀࡁࡓࡀࡄࡉࡌ, romanized: *Abrahim*) is mentioned in Book 18 of the *Right Ginza* as the patriarch of the Jewish people.
[src:infertility/abraham] Mandaeans consider Abraham to have been originally a Mandaean priest, however they differ with Abraham and Jews regarding circumcision which they consider to be bodily mutilation and therefore forbidden.
[src:infertility/abraham] In Christianity, Abraham is revered as the prophet to whom God chose to reveal himself and with whom God initiated a covenant (cf.
[src:infertility/abraham] Paul the Apostle declared that all who believe in Jesus (Christians) are "included in the seed of Abraham and are inheritors of the promise made to Abraham".
[src:infertility/abraham] Throughout history, church leaders, following Paul, have emphasized Abraham as the spiritual father of all Christians.
[src:infertility/abraham] Augustine of Hippo declared that Christians are "children (or 'seed') of Abraham by faith", Ambrose stated that "by means of their faith Christians possess the promises made to Abraham", and Martin Luther recalled Abraham as "a paradigm of the man of faith".
[src:infertility/abraham] The Roman Catholic Church, the largest Christian denomination, calls Abraham "our father in Faith" in the Eucharistic prayer of the Roman Canon, recited during the Mass.
[src:infertility/abraham] In the introduction to his 15th-century translation of the Golden Legend's account of Abraham, William Caxton noted that this patriarch's life was read in church on Quinquagesima Sunday.
[src:infertility/abraham] He is the patron saint of those in the hospitality industry.
[src:infertility/abraham] The Eastern Orthodox Church commemorates him as the "Righteous Forefather Abraham", with two feast days in its liturgical calendar.
[src:infertility/abraham] The first time is on 9 October (for those churches which follow the traditional Julian Calendar, 9 October falls on 22 October of the modern Gregorian Calendar), where he is commemorated together with his nephew "Righteous Lot".
[src:infertility/abraham] The other is on the "Sunday of the Forefathers" (two Sundays before Christmas), when he is commemorated together with other ancestors of Jesus.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham is also mentioned in the Divine Liturgy of Basil the Great, just before the Anaphora, and Abraham and Sarah are invoked in the prayers said by the priest over a newly married couple.
[src:infertility/abraham] A popular hymn sung in many English-speaking Sunday Schools by children is known as "Father Abraham" and emphasizes the patriarch as the spiritual progenitor of Christians.
[src:infertility/abraham] Islam regards *ʾIbrāhīm* (Abraham) as a link in the chain of prophets that begins with Adam and culminates in Muhammad via *ʾIsmāʿīl* (Ishmael).
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham is mentioned in 35 chapters of the Quran, more often than any other biblical personage apart from Moses.
[src:infertility/abraham] He is called both a *hanif* (monotheist) and *muslim* (one who submits), and Muslims regard him as a prophet and patriarch, the archetype of the perfect Muslim, and the revered reformer of the Kaaba in Mecca.
[src:infertility/abraham] Islamic tradition considers Abraham the first "pioneer of Islam" (which is also called *millat ʾIbrāhīm*, the 'religion of Abraham'), and that his purpose and mission throughout his life was to proclaim the oneness of God.
[src:infertility/abraham] In Islam, Abraham holds an exalted position among the major prophets and he is referred to as *Khalīlullāh*, meaning 'Friend of God'.
[src:infertility/abraham] Besides *Ishaq* and *Yaqub* (Isaac and Jacob), Abraham is among the most excellent and honorable men in the view of God.
[src:infertility/abraham] He is also mentioned in Quran as the "Father of Muslims", and is put forward as a role model for the community.
[src:infertility/abraham] The Druze regard Abraham as the third spokesman (*natiq*) after Adam and Noah, who helped transmit the foundational teachings of monotheism (*tawhid*) intended for the larger audience.
[src:infertility/abraham] He is also among the seven prophets who appeared in different periods of history according to the Druze faith.
[src:infertility/abraham] To ʻAbdu'l-Bahá, the Abraham was born to a family that was ignorant of the oneness of God.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham opposed his own people and government, and even his own kin, he rejected all their gods, and, alone and single-handed, he withstood a powerful nation.
[src:infertility/abraham] These people believed not in one God but in many gods, to whom they ascribed miracles, and hence they all rose up against Abraham.
[src:infertility/abraham] No one supported him except his nephew Lot and "one or two other individuals of no consequence".
[src:infertility/abraham] At last the intensity of his enemies' opposition obliged him, utterly wronged, to forsake his native land.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham then came to "these regions", that is, to the Holy Land.
[src:infertility/abraham] To Bahá'u'lláh, the "Voice of God" commanded Abraham to offer up Ishmael as a sacrifice, so that his steadfastness in the faith of God and his detachment from all else but him may be demonstrated unto men.
[src:infertility/abraham] The purpose of God, moreover, was to sacrifice him as a ransom for the sins and iniquities of all the peoples of the earth.
[src:infertility/abraham] In the Baháʼí texts, like the Islamic texts, Abraham is often referred to as "the Friend of God".
[src:infertility/abraham] 'Abdu'l-Bahá described Abraham as the founder of monotheism.
[src:infertility/abraham] ʻAbdu'l-Bahá also suggested the "holy manifestations who have been the sources or founders of the various religious systems" were united and agreed in purpose and teaching, and the Abraham, Moses, Zoroaster, the Buddha, Jesus, Muhammad, the Báb and Bahá'u'lláh are one in "spirit and reality".
[src:infertility/abraham] Paintings on the life of Abraham tend to focus on only a few incidents: the sacrifice of Isaac; meeting Melchizedek; entertaining the three angels; Hagar in the desert; and a few others.
[src:infertility/abraham] Additionally, Martin O'Kane, a professor of Biblical Studies, writes that the parable of Lazarus resting in the "Bosom of Abraham", as described in the Gospel of Luke, became an iconic image in Christian works.
[src:infertility/abraham] According to O'Kane, artists often chose to divert from the common literary portrayal of Lazarus sitting next to Abraham at a banquet in Heaven and instead focus on the "somewhat incongruous notion of Abraham, the most venerated of patriarchs, holding a naked and vulnerable child in his bosom".
[src:infertility/abraham] Several artists have been inspired by the life of Abraham, including Albrecht Dürer (1471–1528), Caravaggio (1573–1610), Donatello, Raphael, Philip van Dyck (Dutch painter, 1680–1753), and Claude Lorrain (French painter, 1600–1682).
[src:infertility/abraham] The Sarcophagus of Junius Bassus depicts a set of biblical stories, including Abraham about to sacrifice Isaac.
[src:infertility/abraham] These sculpted scenes are on the outside of a marble Early Christian sarcophagus used for the burial of Junius Bassus.
[src:infertility/abraham] This sarcophagus has been described as "probably the single most famous piece of early Christian relief sculpture." The sarcophagus was originally placed in or under Old St.
[src:infertility/abraham] Peter's Basilica, was rediscovered in 1597, and is now below the modern basilica in the Museo Storico del Tesoro della Basilica di San Pietro (Museum of St.
[src:infertility/abraham] The base is approximately 4 ft × 8 ft × 4 ft (1.2 m × 2.4 m × 1.2 m).
[src:infertility/abraham] George Segal created figural sculptures by molding plastered gauze strips over live models in his 1987 work *Abraham's Farewell to Ishmael*.
[src:infertility/abraham] The human condition was central to his concerns, and Segal used the Old Testament as a source for his imagery.
[src:infertility/abraham] This sculpture depicts the dilemma faced by Abraham when Sarah demanded that he expel Hagar and Ishmael.
[src:infertility/abraham] In the sculpture, the father's tenderness, Sarah's rage, and Hagar's resigned acceptance portray a range of human emotions.
[src:infertility/abraham] The sculpture was donated to the Miami Art Museum after the artist's death in 2000.
[src:infertility/abraham] Abraham can sometimes be identified by the context of the image – the meeting with Melchizedek, the three visitors, or the sacrifice of Isaac.
[src:infertility/abraham] In solo portraits a sword or knife may be used as his accessory, as in this statue by Giovanni Maria Morlaiter or this painting by Lorenzo Monaco.
[src:infertility/abraham] As early as the beginning of the 3rd century, Christian art followed Christian typology in making the sacrifice of Isaac a foreshadowing of Christ's sacrifice on the cross, and its memorial in the sacrifice of the Mass.
[src:infertility/abraham] See for example this 11th-century Christian altar engraved with Abraham's and other sacrifices taken to prefigure that of Christ in the Eucharist.
[src:infertility/abraham] Some early Christian writers interpreted the three visitors as the triune God.
[src:infertility/abraham] Thus in Santa Maria Maggiore, Rome, a 5th-century mosaic portrays only the visitors against a gold ground and puts semitransparent copies of them in the "heavenly" space above the scene.
[src:infertility/abraham] In Eastern Orthodox art, the visit is the chief means by which the Trinity is pictured (example).
[src:infertility/abraham] Some images do not include Abraham and Sarah, like Andrei Rublev's *Trinity*, which shows only the three visitors as beardless youths at a table.
[src:infertility/abraham] In 1681, Marc-Antoine Charpentier released a Dramatic motet (Oratorio), **Sacrificim Abrahae** H.402 – 402 a – 402 b, for soloists, chorus, doubling instruments and continuo.
[src:infertility/abraham] Sébastien de Brossard composed a cantata **Abraham ou le sacrifice d'Isaac** between 1703 and 1708.
[src:infertility/abraham] In 1994, Steve Reich released an opera named *The Cave*.
[src:infertility/abraham] The title refers to the Cave of the Patriarchs.
[src:infertility/abraham] The narrative of the opera is based on the story of Abraham, and his immediate family, as it is recounted in religious texts, and understood by individuals from different cultures and religious traditions.
[src:infertility/abraham] The eponymous track on Bob Dylan's 1965 album *Highway 61 Revisited* contains five stanzas, with someone in each describing an unusual problem that is ultimately resolved on Highway 61.
[src:infertility/abraham] In the first stanza, God tells Abraham to "kill me a son".
[src:infertility/abraham] God wants the killing done on Highway 61.
[src:infertility/abraham] *Abram*, the birth name of Abraham, is also the name of Dylan's father.
[src:infertility/abraham] In 2004, *Rolling Stone* magazine ranked "Highway 61 Revisited" at number 364 in their 500 Greatest Songs of All Time.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] This treatment is regarded as a form of violence against women and a violation of women's rights.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] It is a recurring issue in facilities around the globe, according to World Health Organization studies, and can have serious consequences for mother and child.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Namely, abuse during childbirth may prevent women from seeking pre-natal care and using other health care services in the future.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Adolescents, unmarried women, women of low socioeconomic status, migrant women, women infected with HIV, and ethnic minority women are at a greater risk of experiencing obstetric violence.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] The World Health Organization notes that abuse during childbirth has yet to be conclusively defined or measured scientifically.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] However, abuse during childbirth is generally defined as neglectful, physical abusive, and/or disrespectful treatment from healthcare professionals towards patients in childbirth.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Such mistreatment is regarded as a violation of the woman's human rights.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Abuse during childbirth can occur over a wide spectrum and may be seen in the forms of non-confidential care, non-dignified care, discrimination, overt physical abuse, non-consented care, abandonment of care, and/or detention in facilities.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Investigations into the prevalence of abusive practices in childbirth have been conducted by the World Health Organization.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Their studies demonstrate that women giving birth in medical facilities experience disrespectful, abusive, and/or neglectful treatment frequently and globally.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] A 2020 study centered in Ghana, Guinea, Myanmar, and Nigeria found that more than 40% of observed women and 35% of surveyed women experienced mistreatment while in childbirth.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Furthermore, adolescents, migrant women, women infected with HIV, and ethnic minority women were deemed more likely than others to experience abuse during childbirth.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Several systemic and sociocultural barriers continue to place women at a disadvantage in society.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] These include antiquated gender roles that cause physicians and others to view women as weak or vulnerable.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Women in childbirth are very vulnerable and often cannot protect themselves against mistreatment, so the consequences of obstetric violence can be serious for both the mother and the child.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] It is often difficult to escape the gender bias in healthcare, which causes women to feel unsafe when considering asking for help or ways to protect themselves.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] The abusive relationship that forms between a woman and her healthcare providers as a result of abuse during childbirth often leads to the woman developing a general mistrust of healthcare services.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Furthermore, consequences can be extended to include a reluctance to seek pre-natal care, medical assistance during childbirth, and other health care services in the future.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Some sources refer to North American obstetricians and gynecologists, especially between the 1950s and 1980s, practicing what was called the *husband's stitch*, which involves placing extra stitches in the woman's vagina after the episiotomy or the natural tearing that occurs during childbirth.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] This procedure was supposedly performed to increase the husband's future sexual pleasure and often caused long-term pain and discomfort for the woman.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] There is no proof that such a practice was widespread in North America, but mentions of it frequently appear in studies about episiotomy in certain American countries such as Brazil.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] There has been a more recent highlight on North American doctors' treatment of pregnant women.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] The growing idea is that there has been a "redressing" of obstetric violence and that women's right to choice has been compromised in some situations.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] In instances where the lives of the woman and the fetus are endangered, the woman has the right to refuse care through procedures such as caesarean section, episiotomy, or vacuum-assisted delivery.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Women are often coerced into having these invasive procedures, even though such coercion has been found to cause long-lasting damage, with many women comparing the experience to rape.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] The term "obstetric violence" is particularly used in Latin American countries, where the law prohibits such mistreatment.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] These laws exist in several Latin American countries, including Argentina, Puerto Rico and Venezuela.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Research into obstetric violence at two public hospitals in Mexico, analyzing the birthing experiences for one month of 2012, found that physical abuse, verbal abuse, and discrimination occurred openly throughout the facilities.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Women receiving government-assisted insurance were subjected to the most discrimination from the healthcare professionals.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Tanzania is an African country with a history of abuse during childbirth.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] In 2011, Shannon McMahon and others explored whether or not the supposed interventions to decrease the prevalence of abuse during childbirth had been effective.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] When interviewing women, they initially referred to their experiences as neutral or better.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] However, after being shown the different aspects of abuse, an overwhelming majority of the women actually reported experiencing abuse during childbirth.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] In 2013–2014, Hannah Ratcliffe and others formed a study to explore possible interventions to improve the experiences of women in childbirth.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] They implemented an "open birth day" that facilitated communication between patients and providers and educated them on the procedures surrounding birth.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] The team also implemented a "respectful maternity care workshop" meant to create conversation surrounding respect between health care staff and patients.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] What they found was that this approach was successful in helping reconstruct systems without costing much.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] There was an increase of 60% in satisfaction with women's delivery experience.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] During the same time period as Ratcliffe's study, Stephanie Kujawaki and others did a comparative study of births with and without interventions.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] The baseline for the study was conducted in 2011–2012, and the final half of the study was conducted in 2015.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] What they found is that there was a 66% reduction in abuse and disrespect during childbirth after interventions.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] This study shows that community and health system reforms can help change and reshape norms in which women are mistreated during childbirth.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] In 2014–2015, Shreeporna Bhattacharya and T.K.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Sundari Ravindran set out to quantitatively determine the prevalence of abuse during childbirth in the Varanasi district of northern India through the use of a questionnaire.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Two rural blocks in the Varanasi district with high rates of institutional deliveries were the focus of the study, with subjects selected randomly from the women who lived in the area.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Bhattacharya and Ravindran report that the frequency at which abusive behavior occurred was 28.8%, with "abusive behavior" acting as a general term.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] The two most common forms of abuse were non-dignified care (19.3%) and physical abuse (13.4%).
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Furthermore, 8.5% of patients reported being neglected or abandoned, 5.6% experienced non-confidential care, and 4.9% faced humiliation due to a lack of cleanliness.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] The authors also note that 90.5% of subjects were met with inappropriate demands for money.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] In terms of correlation, there was no significant link between socio-economic status and abuse, though women who faced complications during labor were four times as likely to experience abuse in the facilities.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Fatima Alzyoud and colleagues studied abuse during childbirth in Jordan, specifically in the forms of neglect and verbal abuse.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Four government-run Maternal and Child Health Centers were used as the locations of the study, with the subjects being 390 Jordanian women aged 18–45.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] The Childbirth Verbal Abuse and Neglect Scale (CVANS) found that 32.2% of the subjects experienced neglect and 37.7% faced verbal abuse during their last childbirth.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Furthermore, there was a negative correlation between age and neglect/verbal abuse.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] While global maternal health research and advocacy have brought recent awareness to obstetric violence, historians have noted historical examples.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] In the United States of America, historians attest that it began during slavery, where enslaved women were physically exploited and experimented on by Antebellum physicians looking to advance the fields of obstetrics and gynaecology.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Later, historians confirm that this took the form of forced sterilizations of black and other women of color as part of the eugenics movement.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Mississippi appendectomies refer to the experience of forced and coerced sterilization of Black women between 1920 and 1980.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Coined by activist Fannie Lou Hamer, Mississippi appendectomies involved Black and other women of color being sterilized without informed consent, knowledge, and without a valid medical reason.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Hamer recalls having received a hysterectomy, without consent, during a surgery to remove a uterine fibroid, rendering her infertile.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Researchers confirm that hysterectomies and tubal ligations were given to poor black women by medical residents allowed to "practice" surgical skills.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Scholars show that some of these historical forms of disrespectful care have persisted into the 21st century.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] The study concluded that Black mothers and infants were two times as likely to die as white mothers and infants within this tax bracket.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] The researchers also found that the rates of maternal mortality among the richest Black women were just as high among the lowest-income white women.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Another study noted that women of color experience mistreatment more frequently than other races, with rates of mistreatment consistently higher for them when compared to white counterparts.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] Though studies have found that the impacts of obstetric violence are disproportionately distributed, they also show it is not limited to black women alone.
[src:infertility/abuse-during-childbirth] A study conducted during the 1970s found that an estimated one-quarter of Indigenous American women of childbearing age were sterilized in Indian Health Service hospitals.
[src:infertility/accidental-incest] The laws of many jurisdictions void incestuous marriages, even if entered into without awareness of the kinship.
[src:infertility/accidental-incest] If an incestuous relationship is suspected, DNA testing may be used.
[src:infertility/accidental-incest] Some jurisdictions permit offspring of IVF donations access to donation records or to adoption records.
[src:infertility/accidental-incest] People may be unaware of a kinship relationship between them in a number of circumstances.
[src:infertility/accidental-incest] For example, artificial insemination with an anonymous donated sperm may result in offspring being unaware of any biological relations, such as paternity or half siblings.
[src:infertility/accidental-incest] To reduce the likelihood of accidental incest, fertility clinics usually limit the number of times that a donor's sperm may be used.
[src:infertility/accidental-incest] Some countries have laws limiting the number of children a donor can father, while others limit sperm donations based on family numbers to enable one family to have true siblings.
[src:infertility/accidental-incest] Taiwan allows those conceived by artificial means to find out if they are related to a person they are considering marrying.
[src:infertility/accidental-incest] Genetic sexual attraction is an unproven hypothesis, commonly considered pseudoscience, offered as an explanation for cases of sexual attraction and relations between adults who were not aware of their close blood relations.
[src:infertility/accidental-incest] In 2008, during a debate on the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Act 2008 in the House of Lords, Lord Alton of Liverpool claimed that a British brother and sister, who were twins separated at birth, married without knowing of their relationship.
[src:infertility/accidental-incest] According to Lord Alton, the relationship was discovered soon after their wedding, and the marriage was annulled.
[src:infertility/accidental-incest] The case was raised regarding whether adoptions should be kept secret.
[src:infertility/accidental-incest] Questions were raised about whether the story is actually true, as Lord Alton was known to oppose the act due to its provision allowing the creation and use of animal-human hybrid stem cells for medical purposes.
[src:infertility/accidental-incest] An engaged couple in South Africa, who had been together for five years and were expecting a child, discovered that they were brother and sister just before their wedding.
[src:infertility/accidental-incest] They were raised separately and met as adults in college.
[src:infertility/accidental-incest] Just before the wedding, their parents met and they came to realize that they were siblings.
[src:infertility/accidental-incest] The couple broke off the relationship after the discovery.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] For fertilization to happen between a sperm and egg cell, a sperm must first fuse with the plasma membrane and then penetrate the female egg cell to fertilize it.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] While the fusion of the sperm cell with the egg cell's plasma membrane is relatively straightforward, penetrating the egg's protective layers, such as the zona pellucida, presents a significant challenge.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Therefore, sperm cells go through a process known as the **acrosome reaction**, which is the reaction that occurs in the acrosome of the sperm as it approaches the egg.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] The acrosome is a membrane-bound organelle of Golgi apparatus origin, commonly located at the tip of the head of the mature spermatozoon, which contains a variety of enzymes and antigens required for fertilization.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] It was once called "apical body" because of its location, or "perforatorium" on the assumption that it might assist the spermatozoon boring into the egg.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] As the sperm approaches the zona pellucida of the egg, which is necessary for initiating the acrosome reaction, the membrane surrounding the acrosome fuses with the plasma membrane of the sperm's head, exposing the contents of the acrosome.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] The contents include surface antigens necessary for binding to the egg's cell membrane, and numerous enzymes which are responsible for breaking through the egg's tough coating and allowing fertilization to occur.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] There are considerable species variations in the morphology and consequences of the acrosome reaction.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] In several species, the trigger for the acrosome reaction has been identified in a layer that surrounds the egg.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] In some echinoderms, a protuberance (the acrosomal process) forms at the apex of the sperm head, supported by a core of actin microfilaments.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] The membrane at the tip of the acrosomal process fuses with the egg's plasma membrane.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] In some echinoderms, including starfish and sea urchins, a significant portion of the exposed acrosomal content contains a protein that temporarily holds the sperm on the egg's surface.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] In mammals, the acrosome reaction releases hyaluronidase and acrosin; their role in fertilization is not yet clear.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] The acrosomal reaction is initiated when sperm comes into contact with the oocyte's zona pellucida.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Upon coming into contact with the zona pellucida, the acrosomal enzymes begin to dissolve, and the actin filament comes into contact with the zona pellucida.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Once the two meet, a calcium influx occurs, causing a signaling cascade.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] The cortical granules inside the oocyte then fuse to the outer membrane, and a quick fast block reaction occurs.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Furthermore, the cortical granules inside the oocyte fuse with the outer membrane, initiating a rapid block reaction.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] This reaction alters a patch of pre-existing sperm plasma membrane, facilitating fusion with the egg plasma membrane.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] A sperm penetration assay includes an acrosome reaction test that assesses how well a sperm can perform during the fertilization process.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Sperm that are unable to go through the acrosome reaction properly will not be able to fertilize an egg.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] However, this problem only occurs in about 5% of men that have the test done.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] This test is rather expensive and provides limited information on a man's fertility.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] In other cases, such as in the wood mouse Apodemus sylvaticus, premature acrosome reactions have been found to cause increased motility in aggregates of spermatozoa promoting fertilization.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] The acrosomal reaction typically occurs in the ampulla of the fallopian tube, the site of fertilization, when the sperm penetrates the secondary oocyte.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Prior events prepare for the acrosome reaction.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] The sperm cell undergoes a series of changes, including acquiring a "hyperactive motility pattern" where its flagellum produces vigorous whip-like movements propelling the sperm through the cervical canal and uterine cavity until it reaches the isthmus of the fallopian tube.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Various mechanisms, including chemotaxis, aid the sperm in approaching the ovum in the ampulla of the fallopian tube.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Once in close proximity, glycoproteins on the outer surface of the sperm bind with glycoproteins on the zona pellucida of the ovum.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Sperm that fail to initiate the acrosome reaction prior to reaching to the zona pellucida are unable to penetrate the zona pellucida.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Since the acrosome reaction has already occurred, sperm are then able to penetrate the zona pellucida due to mechanical action of the tail, not because of the acrosome reaction itself.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] The first stage is the penetration of corona radiata, by releasing hyaluronidase from the acrosome to digest cumulus cells surrounding the oocyte and exposing acrosin attached to the inner membrane of the sperm.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] The cumulus cells are embedded in a gel-like substance made primarily of hyaluronic acid, and developed in the ovary with the egg and support it as it grows.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] The acrosome reaction must occur before the sperm cell reaches the zona pellucida.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Acrosin, once exposed, digests the zona pellucida and membrane of the oocyte, allowing for penetration to happen.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Part of the sperm's cell membrane then fuses with the egg cell's membrane, and the contents of the head sink into the egg.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] In the mouse, it has been demonstrated that ZP3, one of the proteins that make up the zona pellucida, binds to a partner molecule (to the β1,4-galactosyl transferase receptors) on the sperm.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] This lock-and-key type mechanism is species-specific and prevents the sperm and egg of different species from fusing.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] The zona pellucida also releases Ca granules to prevent other sperm from binding.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] There is some evidence that this binding is what triggers the acrosome to release the enzymes that allow the sperm to fuse with the egg.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] A similar mechanism likely occurs in other mammals, but the diversity of zona proteins across species means that the relevant protein and receptor may differ.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] More recent scientific evidence demonstrates that the acrosomal reaction is necessary to expose a protein called IZUMO1 on the sperm: without the reaction, sperm can still penetrate through the zona pellucida to the egg membrane, but cannot fuse.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] As seen in mouse studies, IZUMO1 binds to the oocyte protein JUNO and once bound together, the sperm and the egg fuse together to form two pronuclei.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] These pronuclei supply the zygote with the genetic material necessary for the formation of an embryo.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Additionally, once the fusion of the sperm and oocyte is complete, phospholipase C zeta is released from the sperm.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Following penetration and fusion, if all is normally occurring, the process of egg-activation occurs facilitated by proteins like phospholipase C zeta, and the oocyte is said to have become activated.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] This is thought to be induced by a specific protein phospholipase c zeta.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] It undergoes its secondary meiotic division, and the two haploid nuclei (paternal and maternal) fuse to form a zygote.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] To prevent polyspermy and minimize the possibility of producing a triploid zygote, several changes to the egg's cell membranes render them impenetrable shortly after the first sperm enters the egg (such as the rapid loss of JUNO).
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Spermatozoa can initiate the acrosomal reaction well in advance of reaching the zona pellucida, as well as *in vitro* in an appropriate culture medium.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] This is referred to as spontaneous acrosome reaction (SAR).
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] It is now known that, in a certain sense, this phenomenon is physiologically normal across mammalian species.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] The acrosome reaction is induced by passage through the cumulus oophorus cells, mediated by the hormones they secrete (such as progesterone, LPA, LPC).
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] However, the physiological role of truly spontaneous acrosomal reaction, occurring well before this point in the female reproductive tract, or *in vitro*, is a separate phenomenon.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] In mice, it has been well established as physiologically normal and common.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Mouse sperm which have undergone fully spontaneous acrosome reaction are still able to fertilize eggs.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Furthermore, the rate of spontaneous acrosome reaction is higher in more promiscuous species such as *Apodemus sylvaticus*, which face a high level of sperm competition.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] In humans, on the other hand, it remains disputed where exactly the acrosome reaction is initiated in physiological fertilization, due to experimental constraints (for example, animal studies may make use of transgenic mice with fluorescent sperm, while human studies cannot).
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Studies have been done with the intent of linking *in vitro* SAR rate in human sperm to sperm quality and fertilization rate, but as of 2018, the overall results have been mixed, and do not seem to be clinically informative.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] When using intracytoplasmic sperm injection (ICSI) for IVF, the implantation rate is higher in oocytes injected with spermatozoa that have undergone acrosome reaction (~40%) vs. those injected with nonreacted spermatozoa (~10%).
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] The implantation rate is ~25% in when injected with both reacted and nonreacted spermatozoa.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] The delivery rate per cycle follows the same trend.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] The acrosome reaction can be stimulated in vitro by substances a sperm cell may encounter naturally, such as progesterone or follicular fluid, as well as the more commonly used calcium ionophore A23187.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Birefringence microscopy, flow cytometry or fluorescence microscopy can be used for assessing the shedding of the acrosome or "acrosome reaction" of a sperm sample.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Flow cytometry and fluorescence microscopy are usually done after staining with a fluoresceinated lectin such as FITC-PNA, FITC-PSA, FITC-ConA, or fluoresceinated antibody such as FITC-CD46.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] The antibodies/lectins have a high specificity for different parts of the acrosomal region, and will only bind to a specific site (acrosomal content/ inner/outer membrane).
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] If bound to a fluorescent molecule, regions where these probes have bound can be visualised.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Sperm cells with artificially induced acrosome reactions may serve as positive controls.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] For fluorescence microscopy, a smear of washed sperm cells is made, air-dried, permeabilized, and then stained.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] Such a slide is then viewed under the light of a wavelength that will cause the probe to fluoresce if it is bound to the acrosomal region.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] At least 200 cells are considered arbitrarily and classified as either acrosome intact (fluorescing bright green), or acrosome reacted (no probe present, or only on the equatorial region).
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] It is then expressed as a percentage of the counted cells.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] For assessment with flow cytometry, the washed cells are incubated with the chosen probe, possibly passed again, then sampled in a flow cytometer.
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] After gating the cell population according to forward- and side-scatter, the resulting data can be analyzed (E.g. mean fluorescences compared).
[src:infertility/acrosome-reaction] With this technique, a probe for viability such as propidium iodide (PI) could also be included in order to exclude dead cells from the acrosome assessment, since many sperm cells will spontaneously lose their acrosome when they die.
[src:infertility/infertility] In biology, **infertility** is the inability of a male and female organism to reproduce.
[src:infertility/infertility] It is usually not the natural state of a healthy organism that has reached sexual maturity, so children who have not undergone puberty, which is the body's start of reproductive capacity, are excluded.
[src:infertility/infertility] It is also a normal state in women after menopause.
[src:infertility/infertility] In humans, *infertility* is defined as the inability to become pregnant after at least one year of unprotected and regular sexual intercourse involving a male and female partner.
[src:infertility/infertility] There are many causes of infertility, including some that medical intervention can treat.
[src:infertility/infertility] Estimates from 1997, suggest that worldwide about five percent of all heterosexual couples have an unresolved problem with infertility.
[src:infertility/infertility] That figure has been on the rise, with the World Health Organization (WHO) reporting in 2023 that about 17.5% of people experience infertility during their lifetime, while prevalence at a given time point is 12.6%.
[src:infertility/infertility] Many more couples, however, experience involuntary childlessness for at least one year, with estimates ranging from 12% to 28%.
[src:infertility/infertility] Male infertility is responsible for 20–30% of infertility cases, while 20–35% are due to female infertility, and 25–40% are due to combined problems in both partners.
[src:infertility/infertility] The most common causes of female infertility are hormonal in nature, including low estrogen, imbalanced GnRH secretion, PCOS, and aging, which generally manifests in sparse or absent menstrual periods leading up to menopause.
[src:infertility/infertility] As women age, the number of ovarian follicles and oocytes (eggs) decline, leading to a reduced ovarian reserve.
[src:infertility/infertility] Some women undergo primary ovarian insufficiency (also known as premature menopause) or the loss of ovarian function before age 40, leading to infertility.
[src:infertility/infertility] 85% of infertile couples have an identifiable cause, and 15% is designated unexplained infertility.
[src:infertility/infertility] Of the 85% of identified infertility, 25% is due to disordered ovulation (of which 70% of the cases are due to polycystic ovarian syndrome).
[src:infertility/infertility] Tubal infertility (structural issues with the fallopian tubes) is responsible for 11–67% of infertility in women of childbearing age, with the large range in prevalence due to different populations studied.
[src:infertility/infertility] Endometriosis, the presence of endometrial tissue (which normally lines the uterus) outside of the uterus, accounts for 25–40% of female infertility.
[src:infertility/infertility] Women who are fertile experience a period of fertility before and during ovulation, and are infertile for the rest of the menstrual cycle.
[src:infertility/infertility] Fertility awareness methods are used to discern when these changes occur by tracking changes in cervical mucus or basal body temperature.
[src:infertility/infertility] Male infertility is most commonly due to deficiencies in the semen, and semen quality is used as a surrogate measure of male fecundity.
[src:infertility/infertility] Male infertility may also be due to retrograde ejaculation, low testosterone, functional azoospermia (in which sperm is not produced or not produced in enough numbers) and obstructive azoospermia in which the pathway for the sperm (such as the vas deferens) is obstructed.
[src:infertility/infertility] "Demographers tend to define infertility as childlessness in a population of women of reproductive age." The epidemiological definition refers to "trying for" or "time to" a pregnancy, generally in a population of women exposed to a probability of conception.
[src:infertility/infertility] Currently, female fertility normally peaks in young adulthood.
[src:infertility/infertility] It diminishes after age 35, with pregnancy occurring rarely after age 50.
[src:infertility/infertility] A female is most fertile within 24 hours of ovulation.
[src:infertility/infertility] Male fertility peaks usually in young adulthood and declines after age 40.
[src:infertility/infertility] The time needed to pass (during which the couple tries to conceive) for that couple to be diagnosed with infertility differs between different organizations.
[src:infertility/infertility] Existing definitions of infertility lack uniformity, rendering comparisons in prevalence between countries or over time problematic.
[src:infertility/infertility] Therefore, data estimating the prevalence of infertility cited by various sources differ significantly.
[src:infertility/infertility] A couple that tries unsuccessfully to have a child after a certain period (often a short period, but definitions vary) is sometimes said to be **subfertile**, meaning less fertile than a typical couple.
[src:infertility/infertility] Both infertility and subfertility are defined similarly and often used interchangeably.
[src:infertility/infertility] Subfertility is the delay in conceiving within six to twelve months, whereas infertility is the inability to conceive naturally within a full year.
[src:infertility/infertility] In the UK, previous NICE guidelines defined infertility as failure to conceive after regular unprotected sexual intercourse for two years in the absence of known reproductive pathology.
[src:infertility/infertility] Researchers commonly base demographic studies on infertility prevalence over five years.
[src:infertility/infertility] Primary infertility is defined as the absence of a live birth for women who desire a child and have been in a union for at least 12 months, during which they have not used any contraceptives.
[src:infertility/infertility] The World Health Organization also adds that 'women whose pregnancy spontaneously miscarries, or whose pregnancy results in a stillborn child, without ever having had a live birth, would present with primarily infertility'.
[src:infertility/infertility] Secondary infertility is defined as the difficulty in conceiving a live birth in couples who previously had a child.
[src:infertility/infertility] The consequences of infertility are manifold and can include societal repercussions and personal suffering.
[src:infertility/infertility] Advances in assisted reproductive technologies, such as IVF, can offer hope to many couples where treatment is available.
[src:infertility/infertility] Medical coverage and affordability barriers exist.
[src:infertility/infertility] The medicalization of infertility has unwittingly led to a disregard for the emotional responses that couples experience, which include distress, loss of control, stigmatization, and a disruption in the developmental trajectory of adulthood.
[src:infertility/infertility] One of the main challenges in assessing the distress levels in women with infertility is the accuracy of self-report measures.
[src:infertility/infertility] It is possible that women "fake good" to appear mentally healthier than they are.
[src:infertility/infertility] It is also possible that women feel a sense of hopefulness/increased optimism before initiating infertility treatment, which is when most assessments of distress are collected.
[src:infertility/infertility] Some early studies concluded that infertile women did not report any significant differences in symptoms of anxiety and depression compared to fertile women.
[src:infertility/infertility] The further into treatment a patient goes, the more often they display symptoms of depression and anxiety.
[src:infertility/infertility] Patients with one treatment failure had significantly higher levels of anxiety, and patients with two failures experienced more depression when compared with those without a history of treatment.
[src:infertility/infertility] However, it has also been shown that the more depressed the infertile woman, the less likely she is to start infertility treatment and the more likely she is to drop out after only one cycle.
[src:infertility/infertility] Researchers have also shown that, despite a good prognosis and having the finances available to pay for treatment, discontinuation is most often due to psychological reasons.
[src:infertility/infertility] Fertility does not seem to increase when the women takes antioxidants to reduce the oxidative stress brought by the situation.
[src:infertility/infertility] Infertility may have psychological effects.
[src:infertility/infertility] Parenthood is one of the major transitions in adult life for both men and women.
[src:infertility/infertility] The stress of the non-fulfilment of a wish for a child has been associated with emotional consequences such as anger, depression, anxiety, marital problems, and feelings of worthlessness.
[src:infertility/infertility] Partners may become more anxious to conceive, increasing sexual dysfunction.
[src:infertility/infertility] Marital discord often develops, especially when they are under pressure to make medical decisions.
[src:infertility/infertility] Women trying to conceive often have depression rates similar to those of women who have heart disease or cancer.
[src:infertility/infertility] Emotional stress and marital difficulties are greater in couples where the infertility lies with the man.
[src:infertility/infertility] Male and female partners respond differently to infertility problems.
[src:infertility/infertility] In general, women show higher depression levels than their male partners when dealing with infertility.
[src:infertility/infertility] A possible explanation may be that women feel more responsible and guilty than men during the process of trying to conceive.
[src:infertility/infertility] On the other hand, infertile men experience psychosomatic distress.
[src:infertility/infertility] Having a child is considered to be important in most societies.
[src:infertility/infertility] Infertile couples may experience social and family pressure, leading to a feeling of social isolation.
[src:infertility/infertility] Factors of gender, age, religion, and socioeconomic status are important influences.
[src:infertility/infertility] Societal pressures may affect a couple's decision to approach, avoid, or experience an infertility treatment.
[src:infertility/infertility] Moreover, the socioeconomic status influences the psychology of infertile couples: low socioeconomic status is associated with increased chances of developing depression.
[src:infertility/infertility] In many cultures, the inability to conceive bears a stigma.
[src:infertility/infertility] In closed social groups, a degree of rejection (or a sense of being rejected by the couple) may cause considerable anxiety and disappointment.
[src:infertility/infertility] Some respond by actively avoiding the issue altogether.
[src:infertility/infertility] In the United States, some treatments for infertility, including diagnostic tests, surgery, and therapy for depression, can qualify one for Family and Medical Leave Act leave.
[src:infertility/infertility] It has been suggested that infertility be classified as a form of disability.
[src:infertility/infertility] Couples that suffer from infertility have a higher risk than other couples of developing sexual dysfunctions.
[src:infertility/infertility] The most common sexual issue facing couples is a decline in sexual desire and erectile dysfunction.
[src:infertility/infertility] The most common cause of female infertility is abnormal ovulation, usually manifested by scanty or absent menstrual periods.
[src:infertility/infertility] Iodine deficiency may lead to infertility.
[src:infertility/infertility] Infertility in children is commonly referred to as *prepubescence* (or being *prepubescent*, an adjective used to also refer to humans without secondary sex characteristics).
[src:infertility/infertility] The absence of fertility in children is considered a natural part of human growth and child development, as the hypothalamus in their brain is still underdeveloped and cannot release the hormones required to activate the gonads' gametes.
[src:infertility/infertility] Fertility in children before the ages of eight or nine is considered a disease known as *precocious puberty*.
[src:infertility/infertility] This disease is usually triggered by a brain tumor or other related injury.
[src:infertility/infertility] Delayed puberty, puberty absent past or occurring later than the average onset (between the ages of ten and fourteen), may be a cause of infertility.
[src:infertility/infertility] In the United States, girls are considered to have delayed puberty if they have not started menstruating by age 16 (alongside lacking breast development by age 13).
[src:infertility/infertility] Boys are considered to have delayed puberty if they lack enlargement of the testicles by age 14.
[src:infertility/infertility] Delayed puberty affects about 2% of adolescents.
[src:infertility/infertility] Most commonly, puberty may be delayed for several years and still occur normally, in which case it is considered a constitutional delay of growth and puberty, a common variation of healthy physical development.
[src:infertility/infertility] Delay of puberty may also occur due to various causes such as malnutrition, various systemic diseases, or defects of the reproductive system (hypogonadism) or the body's responsiveness to sex hormones.
[src:infertility/infertility] Antisperm antibodies (ASA) have been considered as an infertility cause in around 10–30% of infertile couples.
[src:infertility/infertility] The antibodies are classified into different groups: IgA, IgG, and IgM.
[src:infertility/infertility] They also differ in the location of the spermatozoon they bind to (head, midpiece, tail).
[src:infertility/infertility] Factors contributing to the formation of antisperm antibodies in women are disturbance of normal immunoregulatory mechanisms, infection, violation of the integrity of the mucous membranes, rape, and unprotected oral or anal sex.
[src:infertility/infertility] Risk factors for the formation of antisperm antibodies in men include the breakdown of the blood‑testis barrier, trauma and surgery, orchitis, varicocele, infections, prostatitis, testicular cancer, failure of immunosuppression and unprotected receptive anal or oral sex with men.
[src:infertility/infertility] Infections with the following sexually transmitted pathogens hurt fertility: *Chlamydia trachomatis* and *Neisseria gonorrhoeae*.
[src:infertility/infertility] There is a consistent association of *Mycoplasma genitalium* infection and female reproductive tract syndromes.
[src:infertility/infertility] *M. genitalium* infection is associated with an increased risk of infertility.
[src:infertility/infertility] Mutations to the NR5A1 gene encoding steroidogenic factor 1 (SF-1) have been found in a small subset of men with non-obstructive male factor infertility, where the cause is unknown.
[src:infertility/infertility] Results of one study investigating a cohort of 315 men revealed changes within the hinge region of SF-1 and no rare allelic variants in fertile control men.
[src:infertility/infertility] Affected individuals displayed more severe forms of infertility such as azoospermia and severe oligozoospermia.
[src:infertility/infertility] Small supernumerary marker chromosomes are abnormal extra chromosomes; they are three times more likely to occur in infertile individuals and account for 0.125% of all infertility cases.
[src:infertility/infertility] See Infertility associated with small supernumerary marker chromosomes and Genetics of infertility#Small supernumerary marker chromosomes and infertility.
[src:infertility/infertility] Other diseases such as chlamydia, and gonorrhea can also cause infertility, due to internal scarring (fallopian tube obstruction).
[src:infertility/infertility] For a woman to conceive, certain things have to happen: vaginal intercourse must take place around the time when an egg is released from her ovary; the system that produces eggs has to be working at optimum levels; and her hormones must be balanced.
[src:infertility/infertility] For women, problems with fertilization arise mainly from either structural problems in the fallopian tube or uterus, or problems releasing eggs.
[src:infertility/infertility] Infertility may be caused by blockage of the fallopian tube due to malformations, infections such as chlamydia, or scar tissue.
[src:infertility/infertility] For example, endometriosis can cause infertility with the growth of endometrial tissue in the fallopian tubes or around the ovaries.
[src:infertility/infertility] Endometriosis is usually more common in women in their mid-twenties and older, especially when childbirth has been postponed.
[src:infertility/infertility] Another major cause of infertility in women may be the inability to ovulate.
[src:infertility/infertility] This is usually related to low levels of the sex hormone estrogen, as well as imbalanced GnRH secretion.
[src:infertility/infertility] Ovulatory disorders make up 25% of the known causes of female infertility.
[src:infertility/infertility] Oligo-ovulation or anovulation results in infertility because no oocyte will be released monthly.
[src:infertility/infertility] In the absence of an oocyte, there is no opportunity for fertilization and pregnancy.
[src:infertility/infertility] Malformation of the eggs themselves may complicate conception.
[src:infertility/infertility] For example, polyendocrine metabolic ovarian syndrome (PMOS) is when the eggs only partially develop within the ovary, and there is an excess of male hormones.
[src:infertility/infertility] Some women are infertile because their ovaries do not mature and release eggs.
[src:infertility/infertility] In this case, synthetic FSH by injection or Clomid (clomiphene citrate) via a pill can be given to stimulate follicular maturation in the ovaries.
[src:infertility/infertility] Other factors that can affect a woman's chances of conceiving include being overweight or underweight, or her age as female fertility declines after the age of 30.
[src:infertility/infertility] Sometimes it can be a combination of factors, and sometimes a clear cause is never established.
[src:infertility/infertility] Male infertility is defined as the inability of a male to make a fertile female pregnant, for a minimum of at least one year of unprotected intercourse.
[src:infertility/infertility] Male infertility is estimated to contribute to 35% of infertility in couples.
[src:infertility/infertility] The main cause of male infertility is low semen quality.
[src:infertility/infertility] In men who have the necessary reproductive organs to procreate, infertility can be caused by low sperm count due to endocrine problems, drugs, radiation, or infection.
[src:infertility/infertility] There may be testicular malformations, hormone imbalance, or blockage of the man's duct system.
[src:infertility/infertility] Although many of these can be treated through surgery or hormonal substitutions, some may be indefinite.
[src:infertility/infertility] Infertility associated with viable, but immotile sperm may be caused by primary ciliary dyskinesia.
[src:infertility/infertility] The sperm must provide the zygote with DNA, centrioles, and an activation factor for the embryo to develop.
[src:infertility/infertility] A defect in any of these sperm structures may result in infertility that will not be detected by semen analysis.
[src:infertility/infertility] Antisperm antibodies cause immune infertility.
[src:infertility/infertility] Cystic fibrosis can lead to infertility in men by blocking the vas deferens.
[src:infertility/infertility] Adeno-associated virus infection has been linked to poor sperm quality and may contribute to male infertility, based on small observational studies.
[src:infertility/infertility] In the US, up to 15% of infertile couples have unexplained infertility, in which no identifiable cause is found.
[src:infertility/infertility] Polymorphisms in folate pathway genes may be a cause for fertility complications in some women with unexplained infertility.
[src:infertility/infertility] Epigenetic modifications in sperm may also be responsible for unexplained infertility.
[src:infertility/infertility] Hybrid animals may have sex-linked infertility, as observed in Haldane's Rule.
[src:infertility/infertility] This phenomenon is likely due to harmful, recessive genes being expressed in individuals with different chromosomes, which reduces fitness and causes infertility.
[src:infertility/infertility] If both partners are young and healthy and have been trying to conceive for one year without success, a visit to a physician or women's health nurse practitioner (WHNP) could help to highlight potential medical problems earlier rather than later.
[src:infertility/infertility] The doctor or WHNP may be able to suggest lifestyle changes to increase the chances of conceiving.
[src:infertility/infertility] A doctor or WHNP takes a medical history and gives a physical examination.
[src:infertility/infertility] They can also carry out some basic tests on both partners to see if there is an identifiable reason for not having achieved a pregnancy.
[src:infertility/infertility] Among these tests, blood tests are common and may include serologies to detect infections such as hepatitis B (HBV), hepatitis C (HCV), HIV, syphilis, and rubella.
[src:infertility/infertility] Optional tests like karyotypes can also be performed.
[src:infertility/infertility] For females, specific tests might include measuring antimüllerian hormone (AMH) to assess ovarian reserve, thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH), prolactin (PRL), and vitamin D levels, which can influence fertility.
[src:infertility/infertility] If necessary, they refer patients to a fertility clinic or local hospital for more specialized tests.
[src:infertility/infertility] The results of these tests help determine the best fertility treatment.
[src:infertility/infertility] Treatment depends on the cause of infertility, but may include counselling, fertility treatments, which include in vitro fertilization.
[src:infertility/infertility] According to ESHRE recommendations, couples with an estimated live birth rate of 40% or higher per year are encouraged to continue aiming for a spontaneous pregnancy.
[src:infertility/infertility] Drugs used include clomiphene citrate, human menopausal gonadotropin (hMG), follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH), human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG), gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) analogues, and aromatase inhibitors.
[src:infertility/infertility] Clomiphene is a selective estrogen receptor modulator used to induce ovulation.
[src:infertility/infertility] It works by blocking the negative feedback from estrogen, creating a gonadotropin releasing hormone (GnRH) increase, which causes the release of luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) from the anterior pituitary.
[src:infertility/infertility] FSH and LH act on the ovaries to increase follicle growth and lead to ovulation.
[src:infertility/infertility] Letrozole is an aromatase inhibitor which reduces estradiol levels and increases levels of FSH and LH, which can stimulate ovarian follicle maturation and ovulation.
[src:infertility/infertility] Letrozole is the preferred treatment in those with infertility due to PCOS and is associated with a higher pregnancy rate than other treatments.
